# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: linear-algebra
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In mathematics, the **cross product** or **vector product** (occasionally **directed area product**, to emphasize its geometric significance) is a binary operation on two vectors in a three-dimensional oriented Euclidean vector space (named here E ), and is denoted by the symbol $\times$ .
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Given two linearly independent vectors **a** and **b**, the cross product, **a** × **b** (read "a cross b"), is a vector that is perpendicular to both **a** and **b**, and thus normal to the plane containing them.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] It has many applications in mathematics, physics, engineering, and computer programming.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] It should not be confused with the dot product (projection product).
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The magnitude of the cross product equals the area of a parallelogram with the vectors for sides; in particular, the magnitude of the product of two perpendicular vectors is the product of their lengths.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The units of the cross-product are the product of the units of each vector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] If two vectors are parallel or are anti-parallel (that is, they are linearly dependent), or if either one has zero length, then their cross product is zero.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The space E together with the cross product is an algebra over the real numbers, which is neither commutative nor associative, but is a Lie algebra with the cross product being the Lie bracket.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Like the dot product, it depends on the metric of the space under consideration, but unlike the dot product, it also depends on a choice of an orientation of the space (this is why the space must be oriented).
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product is invariant under a rotation of the basis but is changed into its opposite by an odd permutation of the basis vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Therefore, the cross product is a pseudovector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In connection with the cross product, the exterior product of vectors can be used in arbitrary dimensions (with a bivector or 2-form result) and is independent of the orientation of the space.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The product can be generalized in various ways, using the orientation and metric structure just as for the traditional 3-dimensional cross product; one can, in n dimensions, take the product of *n* − 1 vectors to produce a vector perpendicular to all of them.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] But if the product is limited to non-trivial binary products with vector results, it exists only in three and seven dimensions.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross-product in seven dimensions has undesirable properties (e.g. it fails to satisfy the Jacobi identity), so it is not used in mathematical physics to represent quantities such as multi-dimensional space-time.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product of two vectors **a** and **b** is defined only in three-dimensional space and is denoted by **a** × **b**.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In physics and applied mathematics, the wedge notation **a** ∧ **b** is often used (in conjunction with the name *vector product*), although in pure mathematics such notation is usually reserved for just the exterior product, an abstraction of the vector product to n dimensions.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product **a** × **b** is defined as a vector **c** that is perpendicular (orthogonal) to both **a** and **b**, with a direction given by the right-hand rule and a magnitude equal to the area of the parallelogram that the vectors span.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] If the vectors **a** and **b** are parallel (that is, the angle *θ* between them is either 0° or 180°), by the above formula, the cross product of **a** and **b** is the zero vector **0**.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The direction of the vector **n** depends on the chosen orientation of the space.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Conventionally, it is given by the right-hand rule, where one simply points the forefinger of the right hand in the direction of **a** and the middle finger in the direction of **b**.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Then, the vector **n** is coming out of the thumb (see the adjacent picture).
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Using this rule implies that the cross product is anti-commutative; that is, **b** × **a** = −(**a** × **b**).
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] By pointing the forefinger toward **b** first, and then pointing the middle finger toward **a**, the thumb will be forced in the opposite direction, reversing the sign of the product vector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] As the cross product operator depends on the orientation of the space, in general the cross product of two vectors is not a "true" vector, but a pseudovector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In 1842, William Rowan Hamilton first described the algebra of quaternions and the non-commutative Hamilton product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In particular, when the Hamilton product of two vectors (that is, pure quaternions with zero scalar part) is performed, it results in a quaternion with a scalar and vector part.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The scalar and vector part of this Hamilton product corresponds to the negative of dot product and cross product of the two vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In 1881, Josiah Willard Gibbs, and independently Oliver Heaviside, introduced the notation for both the dot product and the cross product using a period (**a** ⋅ **b**) and an "×" (**a** × **b**), respectively, to denote them.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In 1877, to emphasize the fact that the result of a dot product is a scalar while the result of a cross product is a vector, William Kingdon Clifford coined the alternative names **scalar product** and **vector product** for the two operations.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] These alternative names are still widely used in the literature.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Both the cross notation (**a** × **b**) and the name *cross product* were possibly inspired by the fact that each scalar component of **a** × **b** is computed by multiplying non-corresponding components of **a** and **b**.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Conversely, a dot product **a** ⋅ **b** involves multiplications between corresponding components of **a** and **b**.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] As explained below, the cross product can be expressed in the form of a determinant of a special 3 × 3 matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] According to Sarrus's rule, this involves multiplications between matrix elements identified by crossed diagonals.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This mnemonic applies also to many formulas given in this article.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] These equalities, together with the distributivity and linearity of the cross product (though neither follows easily from the definition given above), are sufficient to determine the cross product of any two vectors **a** and **b**.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This can be interpreted as the decomposition of **a** × **b** into the sum of nine simpler cross products involving vectors aligned with **i**, **j**, or **k**.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Each one of these nine cross products operates on two vectors that are easy to handle as they are either parallel or orthogonal to each other.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This determinant can be computed using Sarrus's rule or cofactor expansion.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] which gives the components of the resulting vector directly.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The latter formula avoids having to change the orientation of the space when we inverse an orthonormal basis.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Because the magnitude of the cross product goes by the sine of the angle between its arguments, the cross product can be thought of as a measure of *perpendicularity* in the same way that the dot product is a measure of *parallelism*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Given two unit vectors, their cross product has a magnitude of 1 if the two are perpendicular and a magnitude of zero if the two are parallel.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The dot product of two unit vectors behaves just oppositely: it is zero when the unit vectors are perpendicular and 1 if the unit vectors are parallel.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Unit vectors enable two convenient identities: the dot product of two unit vectors yields the cosine (which may be positive or negative) of the angle between the two unit vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The magnitude of the cross product of the two unit vectors yields the sine (which will always be positive).
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This can be the case where **b** and **c** cancel, but additionally where **a** and **b** − **c** are parallel; that is, they are related by a scale factor *t*, leading to: $\mathbf {c} =\mathbf {b} +t\,\mathbf {a} ,$ for some scalar *t*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] From the geometrical definition, the cross product is invariant under proper rotations about the axis defined by **a** × **b**.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In formulae: $(R\mathbf {a} )\times (R\mathbf {b} )=R(\mathbf {a} \times \mathbf {b} ),$ where R is a rotation matrix with $\det(R)=1$ .
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] It can be readily seen how this formula reduces to the former one if M is a rotation matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] where **a** and **b** are vectors that depend on the real variable *t*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product is used in both forms of the triple product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] It is the signed volume of the parallelepiped with edges **a**, **b** and **c** and as such the vectors can be used in any order that's an even permutation of the above ordering.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The mnemonic "BAC minus CAB" is used to remember the order of the vectors in the right hand member.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This formula is used in physics to simplify vector calculations.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] where ∇2 is the vector Laplacian operator.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The right-hand side is the Gram determinant of **a** and **b**, the square of the area of the parallelogram defined by the vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This condition determines the magnitude of the cross product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] which is the magnitude of the cross product expressed in terms of *θ*, equal to the area of the parallelogram defined by **a** and **b** (see definition above).
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The combination of this requirement and the property that the cross product be orthogonal to its constituents **a** and **b** provides an alternative definition of the cross product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In that case, there exists an infinite family of solutions for **b**, which are $\mathbf {b} ={\frac {\mathbf {c} \times \mathbf {a} }{\left\|\mathbf {a} \right\|^{2}}}+t\mathbf {a} ,$ where *t* is an arbitrary constant.
