[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This also shows that the Riemannian volume form for surfaces is exactly the surface element from vector calculus.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In **R**3, Lagrange's equation is a special case of the multiplicativity |**vw**| = |**v**||**w**| of the norm in the quaternion algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] If **a** = **c** and **b** = **d**, this simplifies to the formula above.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The columns [**a**]×,i of the skew-symmetric matrix for a vector **a** can be also obtained by calculating the cross product with unit vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This result can be generalized to higher dimensions using geometric algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In particular in any dimension bivectors can be identified with skew-symmetric matrices, so the product between a skew-symmetric matrix and vector is equivalent to the grade-1 part of the product of a bivector and vector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In three dimensions bivectors are dual to vectors so the product is equivalent to the cross product, with the bivector instead of its vector dual.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In higher dimensions the product can still be calculated but bivectors have more degrees of freedom and are not equivalent to vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This notation is also often much easier to work with, for example, in epipolar geometry.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The above-mentioned triple product expansion (bac–cab rule) can be easily proven using this notation.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] As mentioned above, the Lie algebra **R**3 with cross product is isomorphic to the Lie algebra **so(3)**, whose elements can be identified with the 3×3 skew-symmetric matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Under this map, the cross product of 3-vectors corresponds to the commutator of 3x3 skew-symmetric matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] where the indices $i,j,k$ correspond to vector components.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] in which repeated indices are summed over the values 1 to 3.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In a positively-oriented orthonormal basis *ηmi* = *δ**mi* (the Kronecker delta) and $E_{ijk}=\varepsilon _{ijk}$ (the Levi-Civita symbol).
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In classical mechanics: representing the cross product by using the Levi-Civita symbol can cause mechanical symmetries to be obvious when physical systems are isotropic.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The word "xyzzy" can be used to remember the definition of the cross product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The second and third equations can be obtained from the first by simply vertically rotating the subscripts, *x* → *y* → *z* → *x*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The problem, of course, is how to remember the first equation, and two options are available for this purpose: either to remember the relevant two diagonals of Sarrus's scheme (those containing ***i***), or to remember the xyzzy sequence.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Since the first diagonal in Sarrus's scheme is just the main diagonal of the above-mentioned 3×3 matrix, the first three letters of the word xyzzy can be very easily remembered.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Similarly to the mnemonic device above, a "cross" or X can be visualized between the two vectors in the equation.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This may be helpful for remembering the correct cross product formula.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] When doing this for $a_{y}$ the next two elements down should "wrap around" the matrix so that after the z component comes the x component.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] For clarity, when performing this operation for $a_{y}$ , the next two components should be z and x (in that order).
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] While for $a_{z}$ the next two components should be taken as x and y.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] For $a_{x}$ then, if we visualize the cross operator as pointing from an element on the left to an element on the right, we can take the first element on the left and simply multiply by the element that the cross points to in the right-hand matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] We then subtract the next element down on the left, multiplied by the element that the cross points to here as well.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] We can do this in the same way for $a_{y}$ and $a_{z}$ to construct their associated formulas.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product has applications in various contexts.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] For example, it is used in computational geometry, physics and engineering.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] A non-exhaustive list of examples follows.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product appears in the calculation of the distance of two skew lines (lines not in the same plane) from each other in three-dimensional space.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product can be used to calculate the normal for a triangle or polygon, an operation frequently performed in computer graphics.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] For example, the winding of a polygon (clockwise or anticlockwise) about a point within the polygon can be calculated by triangulating the polygon (like spoking a wheel) and summing the angles (between the spokes) using the cross product to keep track of the sign of each angle.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In computational geometry of the plane, the cross product is used to determine the sign of the acute angle defined by three points $p_{1}=(x_{1},y_{1}),p_{2}=(x_{2},y_{2})$ and $p_{3}=(x_{3},y_{3})$ .
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] It corresponds to the direction (upward or downward) of the cross product of the two coplanar vectors defined by the two pairs of points $(p_{1},p_{2})$ and $(p_{1},p_{3})$ .
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The sign of the acute angle is the sign of the expression $P=(x_{2}-x_{1})(y_{3}-y_{1})-(y_{2}-y_{1})(x_{3}-x_{1}),$ which is the signed length of the cross product of the two vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] To use the cross product, simply extend the 2D vectors $p_{1},p_{2},p_{3}$ to co-planar 3D vectors by setting $z_{k}=0$ for each of them.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In the "right-handed" coordinate system, if the result is 0, the points are collinear; if it is positive, the three points constitute a positive angle of rotation around $p_{1}$ from $p_{2}$ to $p_{3}$ , otherwise a negative angle.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product is used in calculating the volume of a polyhedron such as a tetrahedron or parallelepiped.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] where **r** is the position vector of the particle relative to the origin, **p** is the linear momentum of the particle.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Since position **r**, linear momentum **p** and force **F** are all *true* vectors, both the angular momentum **L** and the moment of a force **M** are *pseudovectors* or *axial vectors*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product frequently appears in the description of rigid motions.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] where $\mathbf {r}$ is the point's position, $\mathbf {v}$ is its velocity and ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ is the body's angular velocity.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Since position $\mathbf {r}$ and velocity $\mathbf {v}$ are *true* vectors, the angular velocity ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ is a *pseudovector* or *axial vector*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Since velocity **v**, force **F** and electric field **E** are all *true* vectors, the magnetic field **B** is a *pseudovector*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In vector calculus, the cross product is used to define the formula for the vector operator curl.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The trick of rewriting a cross product in terms of a matrix multiplication appears frequently in epipolar and multi-view geometry, in particular when deriving matching constraints.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] The cross product can be defined in terms of the exterior product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] It can be generalized to an external product in other than three dimensions.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This generalization allows a natural geometric interpretation of the cross product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In exterior algebra the exterior product of two vectors is a bivector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] A bivector is an oriented plane element, in much the same way that a vector is an oriented line element.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Given two vectors *a* and *b*, one can view the bivector *a* ∧ *b* as the oriented parallelogram spanned by *a* and *b*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] This can be thought of as the oriented multi-dimensional element "perpendicular" to the bivector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] In a *d-*dimensional space, Hodge star takes a *k*-vector to a (*d–k*)-vector; thus only in *d =* 3 dimensions is the result an element of dimension one (3–2 = 1), i.e. a vector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] For example, in *d =* 4 dimensions, the cross product of two vectors has dimension 4–2 = 2, giving a bivector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p01] Thus, only in three dimensions does cross product define an algebra structure to multiply vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] There are several ways to generalize the cross product to higher dimensions.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] The cross product can be seen as one of the simplest Lie products, and is thus generalized by Lie algebras, which are axiomatized as binary products satisfying the axioms of multilinearity, skew-symmetry, and the Jacobi identity.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] Many Lie algebras exist, and their study is a major field of mathematics, called Lie theory.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] The cross product can also be described in terms of quaternions.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In general, if a vector [*a*1, *a*2, *a*3] is represented as the quaternion *a*1*i* + *a*2*j* + *a*3*k*, the cross product of two vectors can be obtained by taking their product as quaternions and deleting the real part of the result.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] The real part will be the negative of the dot product of the two vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] A cross product for 7-dimensional vectors can be obtained in the same way by using the octonions instead of the quaternions.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] The nonexistence of nontrivial vector-valued cross products of two vectors in other dimensions is related to the result from Hurwitz's theorem that the only normed division algebras are the ones with dimension 1, 2, 4, and 8.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In general dimension, there is no direct analogue of the binary cross product that yields specifically a vector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] There is however the exterior product, which has similar properties, except that the exterior product of two vectors is now a 2-vector instead of an ordinary vector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] As mentioned above, the cross product can be interpreted as the exterior product in three dimensions by using the Hodge star operator to map 2-vectors to vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] The Hodge dual of the exterior product yields an (*n* − 2)-vector, which is a natural generalization of the cross product in any number of dimensions.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] The exterior product and dot product can be combined (through summation) to form the geometric product in geometric algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] As mentioned above, the cross product can be interpreted in three dimensions as the Hodge dual of the exterior product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In any finite *n* dimensions, the Hodge dual of the exterior product of *n* − 1 vectors is a vector.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] So, instead of a binary operation, in arbitrary finite dimensions, the cross product is generalized as the Hodge dual of the exterior product of some given *n* − 1 vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] This generalization is called **external product**.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] The commutator product could be generalised to arbitrary multivectors in three dimensions, which results in a multivector consisting of only elements of grades 1 (1-vectors/true vectors) and 2 (2-vectors/pseudovectors).
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] While the commutator product of two 1-vectors is indeed the same as the exterior product and yields a 2-vector, the commutator of a 1-vector and a 2-vector yields a true vector, corresponding instead to the left and right contractions in geometric algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] The commutator product of two 2-vectors has no corresponding equivalent product, which is why the commutator product is defined in the first place for 2-vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] Furthermore, the commutator triple product of three 2-vectors is the same as the vector triple product of the same three pseudovectors in vector algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] However, the commutator triple product of three 1-vectors in geometric algebra is instead the negative of the vector triple product of the same three true vectors in vector algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] Generalizations to higher dimensions is provided by the same commutator product of 2-vectors in higher-dimensional geometric algebras, but the 2-vectors are no longer pseudovectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] Just as the commutator product/cross product of 2-vectors in three dimensions correspond to the simplest Lie algebra, the 2-vector subalgebras of higher dimensional geometric algebra equipped with the commutator product also correspond to the Lie algebras.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] Also as in three dimensions, the commutator product could be further generalised to arbitrary multivectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In the context of multilinear algebra, the cross product can be seen as the (1,2)-tensor (a mixed tensor, specifically a bilinear map) obtained from the 3-dimensional volume form, a (0,3)-tensor, by raising an index.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In detail, the 3-dimensional volume form defines a product $V\times V\times V\to \mathbf {R} ,$ by taking the determinant of the matrix given by these 3 vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In the same way, in higher dimensions one may define generalized cross products by raising indices of the *n*-dimensional volume form, which is a $(0,n)$ -tensor.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] These products are all multilinear and skew-symmetric, and can be defined in terms of the determinant and parity.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] This is the unique multilinear, alternating product which evaluates to $e_{1}\times \cdots \times e_{n-1}=e_{n}$ , $e_{2}\times \cdots \times e_{n}=e_{1},$ and so forth for cyclic permutations of indices.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] This formula is identical in structure to the determinant formula for the normal cross product in **R**3 except that the row of basis vectors is the last row in the determinant rather than the first.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] If *n* is odd, this modification leaves the value unchanged, so this convention agrees with the normal definition of the binary product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In the case that *n* is even, however, the distinction must be kept.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] This $(n-1)$ -ary form enjoys many of the same properties as the vector cross product: it is alternating and linear in its arguments, it is perpendicular to each argument, and its magnitude gives the hypervolume of the region bounded by the arguments.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] And just like the vector cross product, it can be defined in a coordinate independent way as the Hodge dual of the wedge product of the arguments.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In 1773, Joseph-Louis Lagrange used the component form of both the dot and cross products in order to study the tetrahedron in three dimensions.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In 1843, William Rowan Hamilton introduced the quaternion product, and with it the terms *vector* and *scalar*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] James Clerk Maxwell used Hamilton's quaternion tools to develop his famous electromagnetism equations, and for this and other reasons quaternions for a time were an essential part of physics education.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In 1844, Hermann Grassmann published a geometric algebra not tied to dimension two or three.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] Grassmann developed several products, including a cross product represented then by [uv].
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In 1853, Augustin-Louis Cauchy, a contemporary of Grassmann, published a paper on algebraic keys which were used to solve equations and had the same multiplication properties as the cross product.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In 1878, William Kingdon Clifford, known for a precursor to the Clifford algebra named in his honor, published *Elements of Dynamic*, in which the term *vector product* is attested.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In the book, this product of two vectors is defined to have magnitude equal to the area of the parallelogram of which they are two sides, and direction perpendicular to their plane.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In lecture notes from 1881, Gibbs represented the cross product by $u\times v$ and called it the *skew product*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In 1901, Gibb's student Edwin Bidwell Wilson edited and extended these lecture notes into the textbook *Vector Analysis*.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] Wilson kept the term *skew product*, but observed that the alternative terms *cross product* and *vector product* were more frequent.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] In 1908, Cesare Burali-Forti and Roberto Marcolongo introduced the vector product notation u ∧ v.
[src:linear-algebra/cross-product-p02] This is used in France and other areas until this day, as the symbol $\times$ is already used to denote multiplication and the Cartesian product.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In mathematics, the **determinant** is a scalar-valued function of the entries of a square matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant of a matrix *A* is commonly denoted det(*A*), det *A*, or |*A*|.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Its value characterizes some properties of the matrix and the linear map represented, on a given basis, by the matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In particular, the determinant is nonzero if and only if the matrix is invertible and the corresponding linear map is an isomorphism.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] However, if the determinant is zero, the matrix is referred to as singular, meaning it does not have an inverse.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant is completely determined by the two following properties: the determinant of a product of matrices is the product of their determinants, and the determinant of a triangular matrix is the product of its diagonal entries.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant of an *n* × *n* matrix can be defined in several equivalent ways, the most common being the Leibniz formula, which expresses the determinant as a sum of $n!$ (the factorial of n) signed products of matrix entries.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Determinants can also be defined by some of their properties.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The exchange of two rows multiplies the determinant by −1.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Multiplying a row by a number multiplies the determinant by this number.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Adding a multiple of one row to another row does not change the determinant.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The above properties relating to rows (properties 2–4) may be replaced by the corresponding statements with respect to columns.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant is invariant under matrix similarity.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This implies that, given a linear endomorphism of a finite-dimensional vector space, the determinant of the matrix that represents it on a basis does not depend on the chosen basis.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This allows defining the *determinant* of a linear endomorphism, which does not depend on the choice of a coordinate system.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Determinants occur throughout mathematics.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For example, a matrix is often used to represent the coefficients in a system of linear equations, and determinants can be used to solve these equations (Cramer's rule), although other methods of solution are computationally much more efficient.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Determinants are used for defining the characteristic polynomial of a square matrix, whose roots are the eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In geometry, the signed n-dimensional volume of a n-dimensional parallelepiped is expressed by a determinant, and the determinant of a linear endomorphism determines how the orientation and the n-dimensional volume are transformed under the endomorphism.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This is used in calculus with exterior differential forms and the Jacobian determinant, in particular for changes of variables in multiple integrals.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant has several key properties that can be proved by direct evaluation of the definition for $2\times 2$ -matrices, and that continue to hold for determinants of larger matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] They are as follows: first, the determinant of the identity matrix ${\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\0&1\end{pmatrix}}$ is 1.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This holds similarly if the two columns are the same.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] If the matrix entries are real numbers, the matrix A represents the linear map that maps the basis vectors to the columns of A.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The images of the basis vectors form a parallelogram that represents the image of the unit square under the mapping.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The parallelogram defined by the columns of the above matrix is the one with vertices at (0, 0), (*a*, *c*), (*a* + *b*, *c* + *d*), and (*b*, *d*), as shown in the accompanying diagram.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The absolute value of *ad* − *bc* is the area of the parallelogram, and thus represents the scale factor by which areas are transformed by A.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The absolute value of the determinant together with the sign becomes the signed area of the parallelogram.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The signed area is the same as the usual area, except that it is negative when the angle from the first to the second vector defining the parallelogram turns in a clockwise direction (which is opposite to the direction one would get for the identity matrix).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] To show that *ad* − *bc* is the signed area, one may consider a matrix containing two vectors **u** ≡ (*a*, *c*) and **v** ≡ (*b*, *d*) representing the parallelogram's sides.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The signed area can be expressed as |**u**| |**v**| sin *θ* for the angle *θ* between the vectors, which is simply base times height, the length of one vector times the perpendicular component of the other.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Due to the sine this already is the signed area, yet it may be expressed more conveniently using the cosine of the complementary angle to a perpendicular vector, e.g.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Thus the determinant gives the area scale factor and the orientation induced by the mapping represented by *A*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] When the determinant is equal to one, the linear mapping defined by the matrix preserves area and orientation.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant gives the signed *n*-dimensional volume of this parallelotope, $\det(A)=\pm {\text{vol}}(P),$ and hence describes more generally the *n*-dimensional volume scale factor of the linear transformation produced by *A*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] (The sign shows whether the transformation preserves or reverses orientation.) In particular, if the determinant is zero, then this parallelotope has volume zero and is not fully *n*-dimensional, which indicates that the dimension of the image of *A* is less than *n*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This means that *A* produces a linear transformation which is neither onto nor one-to-one, and so is not invertible.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The entries $a_{1,1}$ etc. are, for many purposes, real or complex numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] As discussed below, the determinant is also defined for matrices whose entries are in a commutative ring.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] There are various equivalent ways to define the determinant of a square matrix *A*, i.e. one with the same number of rows and columns: the determinant can be defined via the Leibniz formula, an explicit formula involving sums of products of certain entries of the matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant can also be characterized as the unique function depending on the entries of the matrix satisfying certain properties.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This approach can also be used to compute determinants by simplifying the matrices in question.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In this expression, each term has one factor from each row, all in different columns, arranged in increasing row order.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For example, *bdi* has *b* from the first row second column, *d* from the second row first column, and *i* from the third row third column.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The signs are determined by how many transpositions of factors are necessary to arrange the factors in increasing order of their columns (given that the terms are arranged left-to-right in increasing row order): positive for an even number of transpositions and negative for an odd number.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For the example of *bdi*, the single transposition of *bd* to *db* gives *dbi,* whose three factors are from the first, second and third columns respectively; this is an odd number of transpositions, so the term appears with negative sign.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This scheme for calculating the determinant of a 3 × 3 matrix does not carry over into higher dimensions.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Generalizing the above to higher dimensions, the determinant of an $n\times n$ matrix is an expression involving permutations and their signatures.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] A permutation of the set $\{1,2,\dots ,n\}$ is a bijective function $\sigma$ from this set to itself, with values $\sigma (1),\sigma (2),\ldots ,\sigma (n)$ exhausting the entire set.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The set of all such permutations, called the symmetric group, is commonly denoted $S_{n}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The Levi-Civita symbol $\varepsilon _{i_{1},\ldots ,i_{n}}$ is defined on the n-tuples of integers in $\{1,\ldots ,n\}$ as 0 if two of the integers are equal, and otherwise as the signature of the permutation defined by the *n-*tuple of integers.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant can be characterized by the following three key properties.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] where the column vector $a_{i}$ (for each *i*) is composed of the entries of the matrix in the *i*-th column.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] 2. $\det \left(I\right)=1$ , where I is an identity matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] If the determinant is defined using the Leibniz formula as above, these three properties can be proved by direct inspection of that formula.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Some authors also approach the determinant directly using these three properties: it can be shown that there is exactly one function that assigns to any $n\times n$ matrix *A* a number that satisfies these three properties.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This also shows that this more abstract approach to the determinant yields the same definition as the one using the Leibniz formula.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] To see this it suffices to expand the determinant by multi-linearity in the columns into a (huge) linear combination of determinants of matrices in which each column is a standard basis vector.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] These determinants are either 0 (if the columns are linearly dependent, by property 3) or else ±1 (by property 1 and 3 - the minus sign appears when the columns are permuted according to an odd permutation), so the linear combination gives the expression above in terms of the Levi-Civita symbol.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] While less technical in appearance, this characterization cannot entirely replace the Leibniz formula in defining the determinant, since without it the existence of an appropriate function is not clear.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] These characterizing properties and their consequences listed above are both theoretically significant, but can also be used to compute determinants for concrete matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In fact, Gaussian elimination can be applied to bring any matrix into upper triangular form, and the steps in this algorithm affect the determinant in a controlled way.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This can be proven by inspecting the Leibniz formula.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This implies that in all the properties mentioned above, the word "column" can be replaced by "row" throughout.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For example, viewing an *n* × *n* matrix as being composed of *n* rows, the determinant is an *n*-linear function.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This key fact can be proven by observing that, for a fixed matrix B , both sides of the equation are alternating and multilinear as a function depending on the columns of A .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Moreover, they both take the value $\det B$ when A is the identity matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The above-mentioned unique characterization of alternating multilinear maps therefore shows this claim.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] A matrix A with entries in a field is invertible precisely if its determinant is nonzero.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This follows from the multiplicativity of the determinant and the formula for the inverse involving the adjugate matrix mentioned below.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In particular, products and inverses of matrices with non-zero determinant (respectively, determinant one) still have this property.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Thus, the set of such matrices (of fixed size n over a field K ) forms a group known as the general linear group $\operatorname {GL} _{n}(K)$ (respectively, a subgroup called the special linear group $\operatorname {SL} _{n}(K)\subset \operatorname {GL} _{n}(K)$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] More generally, the word "special" indicates the subgroup of another matrix group of matrices of determinant one.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Examples include the special orthogonal group (which if *n* is 2 or 3 consists of all rotation matrices), and the special unitary group.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Because the determinant respects multiplication and inverses, it is in fact a group homomorphism from $\operatorname {GL} _{n}(K)$ into the multiplicative group $K^{\times }$ of nonzero elements of K .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This homomorphism is surjective and its kernel is $\operatorname {SL} _{n}(K)$ (the matrices with determinant one).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Hence, by the first isomorphism theorem, this shows that $\operatorname {SL} _{n}(K)$ is a normal subgroup of $\operatorname {GL} _{n}(K)$ , and that the quotient group $\operatorname {GL} _{n}(K)/\operatorname {SL} _{n}(K)$ is isomorphic to $K^{\times }$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The Cauchy–Binet formula is a generalization of that product formula for *rectangular* matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This formula can also be recast as a multiplicative formula for compound matrices whose entries are the determinants of all quadratic submatrices of a given matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Laplace expansion expresses the determinant of a matrix A recursively in terms of determinants of smaller matrices, known as its minors.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The minor $M_{i,j}$ is defined to be the determinant of the $(n-1)\times (n-1)$ matrix that results from A by removing the i -th row and the j -th column.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The expression $(-1)^{i+j}M_{i,j}$ is known as a cofactor.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] which is called the *Laplace expansion along the ith row*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Unwinding the determinants of these $2\times 2$ -matrices gives back the Leibniz formula mentioned above.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Laplace expansion can be used iteratively for computing determinants, but this approach is inefficient for large matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The formula for the determinant of a $2\times 2$ matrix above continues to hold, under appropriate further assumptions, for a block matrix, i.e., a matrix composed of four submatrices $A,B,C,D$ of dimension $m\times m$ , $m\times n$ , $n\times m$ and $n\times n$ , respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] which simplifies to $\det(A)(D-CA^{-1}B)$ when D is a $1\times 1$ matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Both results can be combined to derive Sylvester's determinant theorem, which is also stated below.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] If the blocks are square matrices of the *same* size further formulas hold.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This formula has been generalized to matrices composed of more than $2\times 2$ blocks, again under appropriate commutativity conditions among the individual blocks.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For $A=D$ and $B=C$ , the following formula holds (even if A and B do not commute).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] It is possible to compute the determinant by the block matrices in a fast way with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms in the time $O({n^{\omega }})$ for $~2.37\leq \omega <3$ , by the $LU$ decomposition.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] where *I**m* and *I**n* are the *m* × *m* and *n* × *n* identity matrices, respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] From this general result several consequences follow.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For square matrices A and B of the same size, the matrices $AB$ and $BA$ have the same characteristic polynomials (hence the same eigenvalues).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] A generalization is $\det \left(Z+AWB\right)=\det \left(Z\right)\det \left(W\right)\det \left(W^{-1}+BZ^{-1}A\right)$ (see Matrix determinant lemma), where *Z* is an *m* × *m* invertible matrix and *W* is an *n* × *n* invertible matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant of the sum $A+B$ of two square matrices of the same size is not in general expressible in terms of the determinants of *A* and of *B*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Brunn–Minkowski theorem implies that the nth root of determinant is a concave function, when restricted to Hermitian positive-definite $n\times n$ matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Therefore, if A and B are Hermitian positive-definite $n\times n$ matrices, one has ${\sqrt[{n}]{\det(A+B)}}\geq {\sqrt[{n}]{\det(A)}}+{\sqrt[{n}]{\det(B)}},$ since the nth root of the determinant is a homogeneous function.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant is closely related to two other central concepts in linear algebra, the eigenvalues and the characteristic polynomial of a matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Let A be an $n\times n$ matrix with complex entries.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Then, by the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra, A must have exactly *n* eigenvalues $\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2},\ldots ,\lambda _{n}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The product of all non-zero eigenvalues is referred to as pseudo-determinant.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] From this, one immediately sees that the determinant of a matrix A is zero if and only if 0 is an eigenvalue of A .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In other words, A is invertible if and only if 0 is not an eigenvalue of A .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Here, t is the indeterminate of the polynomial and I is the identity matrix of the same size as A .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] A Hermitian matrix is positive definite if all its eigenvalues are positive.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] being positive, for all k between 1 and n .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The trace tr(*A*) is by definition the sum of the diagonal entries of A and also equals the sum of the eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Here exp(A) denotes the matrix exponential of A, because every eigenvalue λ of A corresponds to the eigenvalue exp(λ) of exp(A).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Such expressions are deducible from combinatorial arguments, Newton's identities, or the Faddeev–LeVerrier algorithm.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This formula can also be used to find the determinant of a matrix *AIJ* with multidimensional indices *I* = (*i*1, *i*2, ..., *ir*) and *J* = (*j*1, *j*2, ..., *jr*).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] An important arbitrary dimension n identity can be obtained from the Mercator series expansion of the logarithm when the expansion converges.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] is expanded as a formal power series in s then all coefficients of sm for *m* > *n* are zero and the remaining polynomial is det(*I* + *sA*).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This relationship can be derived via the formula for the Kullback–Leibler divergence between two multivariate normal distributions.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] These inequalities can be proved by expressing the traces and the determinant in terms of the eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] As such, they represent the well-known fact that the harmonic mean is less than the geometric mean, which is less than the arithmetic mean, which is, in turn, less than the root mean square.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The Leibniz formula shows that the determinant of real (or analogously for complex) square matrices is a polynomial function from $\mathbf {R} ^{n\times n}$ to $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In particular, it is everywhere differentiable.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] where $\operatorname {adj} (A)$ denotes the adjugate of A .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This identity is used in describing Lie algebras associated to certain matrix Lie groups.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For example, the special linear group $\operatorname {SL} _{n}$ is defined by the equation $\det A=1$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The above formula shows that its Lie algebra is the special linear Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {sl}}_{n}$ consisting of those matrices having trace zero.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Historically, determinants were used long before matrices: A determinant was originally defined as a property of a system of linear equations.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant "determines" whether the system has a unique solution (which occurs precisely if the determinant is non-zero).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In Europe, solutions of linear systems of two equations were expressed by Cardano in 1545 by a determinant-like entity.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Determinants proper originated separately from the work of Seki Takakazu in 1683 in Japan and parallelly of Leibniz in 1693.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Cramer (1750) stated, without proof, Cramer's rule.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Both Cramer and also Bézout (1779) were led to determinants by the question of plane curves passing through a given set of points.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Vandermonde (1771) first recognized determinants as independent functions.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Laplace (1772) gave the general method of expanding a determinant in terms of its complementary minors: Vandermonde had already given a special case.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Immediately following, Lagrange (1773) treated determinants of the second and third order and applied it to questions of elimination theory; he proved many special cases of general identities.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Like Lagrange, he made much use of determinants in the theory of numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] He introduced the word "determinant" (Laplace had used "resultant"), though not in the present signification, but rather as applied to the discriminant of a quadratic form.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Gauss also arrived at the notion of reciprocal (inverse) determinants, and came very near the multiplication theorem.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The next contributor of importance is Binet (1811, 1812), who formally stated the theorem relating to the product of two matrices of *m* columns and *n* rows, which for the special case of *m* = *n* reduces to the multiplication theorem.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] On the same day (November 30, 1812) that Binet presented his paper to the Academy, Cauchy also presented one on the subject.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] (See Cauchy–Binet formula.) In this he used the word "determinant" in its present sense, summarized and simplified what was then known on the subject, improved the notation, and gave the multiplication theorem with a proof more satisfactory than Binet's.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] With him begins the theory in its generality.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Jacobi (1841) used the functional determinant which Sylvester later called the Jacobian.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In his memoirs in *Crelle's Journal* for 1841 he specially treats this subject, as well as the class of alternating functions which Sylvester has called *alternants*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] About the time of Jacobi's last memoirs, Sylvester (1839) and Cayley began their work.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Cayley 1841 introduced the modern notation for the determinant using vertical bars.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The study of special forms of determinants has been the natural result of the completion of the general theory.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Of the textbooks on the subject Spottiswoode's was the first.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In America, Hanus (1886), Weld (1893), and Muir/Metzler (1933) published treatises.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Determinants can be used to describe the solutions of a linear system of equations, written in matrix form as $Ax=b$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This equation has a unique solution x if and only if $\det(A)$ is nonzero.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] where $A_{i}$ is the matrix formed by replacing the i -th column of A by the column vector b .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] This follows immediately by column expansion of the determinant, i.e.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] where the vectors $a_{j}$ are the columns of *A*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Cramer's rule can be implemented in $\operatorname {O} (n^{3})$ time, which is comparable to more common methods of solving systems of linear equations, such as LU, QR, or singular value decomposition.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Determinants can be used to characterize linearly dependent vectors: $\det A$ is zero if and only if the column vectors of the matrix A are linearly dependent.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For example, given two linearly independent vectors $v_{1},v_{2}\in \mathbf {R} ^{3}$ , a third vector $v_{3}$ lies in the plane spanned by the former two vectors exactly if the determinant of the $3\times 3$ matrix consisting of the three vectors is zero.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] It is non-zero (for some x ) in a specified interval if and only if the given functions and all their derivatives up to order $n-1$ are linearly independent.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] If it can be shown that the Wronskian is zero everywhere on an interval then, in the case of analytic functions, this implies the given functions are linearly dependent.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] See the Wronskian and linear independence.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] Another such use of the determinant is the resultant, which gives a criterion when two polynomials have a common root.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The computation of a cross product is equivalent to finding the formal determinant a specific 3 by 3 matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant can be thought of as assigning a number to every sequence of *n* vectors in **R***n*, by using the square matrix whose columns are the given vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant will be nonzero if and only if the sequence of vectors is a *basis* for **R***n*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In that case, the sign of the determinant determines whether the orientation of the basis is consistent with or opposite to the orientation of the standard basis.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] In the case of an orthogonal basis, the magnitude of the determinant is equal to the *product* of the lengths of the basis vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For instance, an orthogonal matrix with entries in **R***n* represents an orthonormal basis in Euclidean space, and hence has determinant of ±1 (since all the vectors have length 1).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant is +1 if and only if the basis has the same orientation.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] It is −1 if and only if the basis has the opposite orientation.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] More generally, if the determinant of *A* is positive, *A* represents an orientation-preserving linear transformation (if *A* is an orthogonal 2 × 2 or 3 × 3 matrix, this is a rotation), while if it is negative, *A* switches the orientation of the basis.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] As pointed out above, the absolute value of the determinant of real vectors is equal to the volume of the parallelepiped spanned by those vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] As a consequence, if $f:\mathbf {R} ^{n}\to \mathbf {R} ^{n}$ is the linear map given by multiplication with a matrix A , and $S\subset \mathbf {R} ^{n}$ is any measurable subset, then the volume of $f(S)$ is given by $|\det(A)|$ times the volume of S .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] By calculating the volume of the tetrahedron bounded by four points, they can be used to identify skew lines.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The volume of any tetrahedron, given its vertices $a,b,c,d$ , ${\frac {1}{6}}\cdot |\det(a-b,b-c,c-d)|$ , or any other combination of pairs of vertices that form a spanning tree over the vertices.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] For a general differentiable function, much of the above carries over by considering the Jacobian matrix of *f*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The Jacobian also occurs in the inverse function theorem.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] When applied to the field of Cartography, the determinant can be used to measure the rate of expansion of a map near the poles.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant provides a convenient way to calculate the area of a triangle in the xy-plane.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] where the sign $\pm$ is chosen to yield a positive area.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] An immediate corollary of this result is that if the determinant is zero, there is no triangle, which implies the points are collinear.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p01] The determinant, therefore, provides a useful tool to test for collinearity.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The above identities concerning the determinant of products and inverses of matrices imply that similar matrices have the same determinant: two matrices *A* and *B* are similar, if there exists an invertible matrix *X* such that *A* = *X*−1*BX*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The determinant is therefore also called a similarity invariant.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] for some finite-dimensional vector space *V* is defined to be the determinant of the matrix describing it, with respect to an arbitrary choice of basis in *V*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] By the similarity invariance, this determinant is independent of the choice of the basis for *V* and therefore only depends on the endomorphism *T*.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The above definition of the determinant using the Leibniz rule works more generally when the entries of the matrix are elements of a commutative ring R , such as the integers $\mathbf {Z}$ , as opposed to the field of real or complex numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Moreover, the characterization of the determinant as the unique alternating multilinear map that satisfies $\det(I)=1$ still holds, as do all the properties that result from that characterization.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] A matrix $A\in \operatorname {Mat} _{n\times n}(R)$ is invertible (in the sense that there is an inverse matrix whose entries are in R ) if and only if its determinant is an invertible element in R .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] For $R=\mathbf {Z}$ , this means that the determinant is +1 or −1.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] between the general linear group (the group of invertible $n\times n$ -matrices with entries in R ) and the multiplicative group of units in R .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Since it respects the multiplication in both groups, this map is a group homomorphism.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Given a ring homomorphism $f:R\to S$ , there is a map $\operatorname {GL} _{n}(f):\operatorname {GL} _{n}(R)\to \operatorname {GL} _{n}(S)$ given by replacing all entries in R by their images under f .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] In other words, the displayed commutative diagram commutes.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] In the language of category theory, the determinant is a natural transformation between the two functors $\operatorname {GL} _{n}$ and $(-)^{\times }$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The determinant of a linear transformation $T:V\to V$ of an n -dimensional vector space V or, more generally a free module of (finite) rank n over a commutative ring R can be formulated in a coordinate-free manner by considering the n -th exterior power $\bigwedge ^{n}V$ of V .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] As $\bigwedge ^{n}V$ is one-dimensional, the map $\bigwedge ^{n}T$ is given by multiplying with some scalar, i.e., an element in R .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] This definition agrees with the more concrete coordinate-dependent definition.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] This can be shown using the uniqueness of a multilinear alternating form on n -tuples of vectors in $R^{n}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] For this reason, the highest non-zero exterior power $\bigwedge ^{n}V$ (as opposed to the determinant associated to an endomorphism) is sometimes also called the determinant of V and similarly for more involved objects such as vector bundles or chain complexes of vector spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Minors of a matrix can also be cast in this setting, by considering lower alternating forms $\bigwedge ^{k}V$ with $k<n$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The conventional definition of the determinant, as a sum over permutations over a product of matrix elements, can be written using the somewhat surprising notation of the Berezin integral.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] This holds for any $n\times n$ -dimensional matrix $A.$ The symbols $\theta ,\eta$ are two n -dimensional vectors of anti-commuting Grassmann numbers (aka "supernumbers"), taken from the Grassmann algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The $\exp$ here is the exponential function.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The integral sign is meant to be understood as the Berezin integral.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Despite the use of the integral symbol, this expression is in fact an entirely finite sum.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The anti-commuting property of the Grassmann numbers captures the sign (signature) of the permutation, while the integral combined with the $\exp$ ensures that all permutations are explored.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] That is, the Taylor's series for $\exp$ terminates after exactly n terms, because the square of a Grassmann number is zero, and there are exactly n distinct Grassmann variables.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Meanwhile, the integral is defined to vanish, if the corresponding Grassmann number does *not* appear in the integrand.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Thus, the integral selects out only those terms in the $\exp$ series that have exactly n distinct variables; all lower-order terms vanish.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Thus, the somewhat magical combination of the integral sign, the use of anti-commuting variables, and the Taylor's series for $\exp$ just encodes a finite sum, identical to the conventional summation.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] This form is popular in physics, where it is often used as a stand-in for the Jacobian determinant.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The appeal is that, notationally, the integral takes the form of a path integral, such as in the path integral formulation for quantized Hamiltonian mechanics.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] An example can be found in the theory of Fadeev–Popov ghosts; although this theory may seem rather abstruse, it's best to keep in mind that the use of the ghost fields is little more than a notational trick to express a Jacobian determinant.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The integrand has exactly the same formal structure as a normal Gaussian distribution, albeit with Grassman numbers, instead of real numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] This formal resemblance accounts for the occasional appearance of supernumbers in the theory of stochastic dynamics and stochastic differential equations.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Determinants as treated above admit several variants: the permanent of a matrix is defined as the determinant, except that the factors $\operatorname {sgn}(\sigma )$ occurring in Leibniz's rule are omitted.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The immanant generalizes both by introducing a character of the symmetric group $S_{n}$ in Leibniz's rule.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] This definition proceeds by establishing the characteristic polynomial independently of the determinant, and defining the determinant as the lowest order term of this polynomial.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] the norm $N_{L/F}:L\to F$ of a field extension, as well as the Pfaffian of a skew-symmetric matrix and the reduced norm of a central simple algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] For matrices with an infinite number of rows and columns, the above definitions of the determinant do not carry over directly.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] For example, in the Leibniz formula, an infinite sum (all of whose terms are infinite products) would have to be calculated.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Functional analysis provides different extensions of the determinant for such infinite-dimensional situations, which however only work for particular kinds of operators.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Another infinite-dimensional notion of determinant is the functional determinant.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] For operators in a finite factor, one may define a positive real-valued determinant called the Fuglede−Kadison determinant using the canonical trace.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] In fact, corresponding to every tracial state on a von Neumann algebra there is a notion of Fuglede−Kadison determinant.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] For matrices over non-commutative rings, multilinearity and alternating properties are incompatible for *n* ≥ 2, so there is no good definition of the determinant in this setting.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] For square matrices with entries in a non-commutative ring, there are various difficulties in defining determinants analogously to that for commutative rings.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Over non-commutative rings, there is no reasonable notion of a multilinear form (existence of a nonzero bilinear form with a regular element of *R* as value on some pair of arguments implies that *R* is commutative).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Nevertheless, various notions of non-commutative determinant have been formulated that preserve some of the properties of determinants, notably quasideterminants and the Dieudonné determinant.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] For some classes of matrices with non-commutative elements, one can define the determinant and prove linear algebra theorems that are very similar to their commutative analogs.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Examples include the *q*-determinant on quantum groups, the Capelli determinant on Capelli matrices, and the Berezinian on supermatrices (i.e., matrices whose entries are elements of $\mathbb {Z} _{2}$ -graded rings).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Manin matrices form the class closest to matrices with commutative elements.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Determinants are mainly used as a theoretical tool.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] They are rarely calculated explicitly in numerical linear algebra, where for applications such as checking invertibility and finding eigenvalues the determinant has largely been supplanted by other techniques.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Computational geometry, however, does frequently use calculations related to determinants.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] While the determinant can be computed directly using the Leibniz rule this approach is extremely inefficient for large matrices, since that formula requires calculating $n!$ ( n factorial) products for an $n\times n$ matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Thus, the number of required operations grows very quickly: it is of order $n!$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The Laplace expansion is similarly inefficient.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Therefore, more involved techniques have been developed for calculating determinants.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Gaussian elimination consists of left multiplying a matrix by elementary matrices for getting a matrix in a row echelon form.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] One can restrict the computation to elementary matrices of determinant 1.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] In this case, the determinant of the resulting row echelon form equals the determinant of the initial matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] As a row echelon form is a triangular matrix, its determinant is the product of the entries of its diagonal.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] So, the determinant can be computed for almost free from the result of a Gaussian elimination.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Some methods compute $\det(A)$ by writing the matrix as a product of matrices whose determinants can be more easily computed.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Such techniques are referred to as decomposition methods.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Examples include the LU decomposition, the QR decomposition or the Cholesky decomposition (for positive definite matrices).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] These methods are of order $\operatorname {O} (n^{3})$ , which is a significant improvement over $\operatorname {O} (n!)$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] of a permutation matrix P (which has exactly a single 1 in each column, and otherwise zeros), a lower triangular matrix L and an upper triangular matrix U .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The determinants of the two triangular matrices L and U can be quickly calculated, since they are the products of the respective diagonal entries.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The determinant of P is just the sign $\varepsilon$ of the corresponding permutation (which is $+1$ for an even number of permutations and is $-1$ for an odd number of permutations).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The order $\operatorname {O} (n^{3})$ reached by decomposition methods has been improved by different methods.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] If two matrices of order n can be multiplied in time $M(n)$ , where $M(n)\geq n^{a}$ for some $a>2$ , then there is an algorithm computing the determinant in time $O(M(n))$ .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] This means, for example, that an $\operatorname {O} (n^{2.376})$ algorithm for computing the determinant exists based on the Coppersmith–Winograd algorithm.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] This exponent has been further lowered, as of 2016, to 2.373.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] In addition to the complexity of the algorithm, further criteria can be used to compare algorithms.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Especially for applications concerning matrices over rings, algorithms that compute the determinant without any divisions exist.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] (By contrast, Gauss elimination requires divisions.) One such algorithm, having complexity $\operatorname {O} (n^{4})$ is based on the following idea: one replaces permutations (as in the Leibniz rule) by so-called closed ordered walks, in which several items can be repeated.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] The resulting sum has more terms than in the Leibniz rule, but in the process several of these products can be reused, making it more efficient than naively computing with the Leibniz rule.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Algorithms can also be assessed according to their bit complexity, i.e., how many bits of accuracy are needed to store intermediate values occurring in the computation.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] For example, the Gaussian elimination (or LU decomposition) method is of order $\operatorname {O} (n^{3})$ , but the bit length of intermediate values can become exponentially long.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] By comparison, the Bareiss Algorithm, is an exact-division method (so it does use division, but only in cases where these divisions can be performed without remainder) is of the same order, but the bit complexity is roughly the bit size of the original entries in the matrix times n .
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] If the determinant of *A* and the inverse of *A* have already been computed, the matrix determinant lemma allows rapid calculation of the determinant of *A* + *uv*T, where *u* and *v* are column vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] Lewis Carroll of *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* fame) invented a method for computing determinants called Dodgson condensation.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p02] This method does not always work in its original form.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p03] Thus, the number of required operations grows very quickly: it is of order n ! {\displaystyle n!} ({\displaystyle n!}).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p03] Some methods compute det ( A ) {\displaystyle \det(A)} ({\displaystyle \det(A)}) by writing the matrix as a product of matrices whose determinants can be more easily computed.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p03] These methods are of order O ⁡ ( n 3 ) {\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n^{3})} ({\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n^{3})}), which is a significant improvement over O ⁡ ( n ! ) {\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n!)} ({\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n!)}).
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p03] The determinants of the two triangular matrices L {\displaystyle L} ({\displaystyle L}) and U {\displaystyle U} ({\displaystyle U}) can be quickly calculated, since they are the products of the respective diagonal entries.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p03] The order O ⁡ ( n 3 ) {\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n^{3})} ({\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n^{3})}) reached by decomposition methods has been improved by different methods.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p03] This means, for example, that an O ⁡ ( n 2.376 ) {\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n^{2.376})} ({\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n^{2.376})}) algorithm for computing the determinant exists based on the Coppersmith–Winograd algorithm.
[src:linear-algebra/determinant-p03] For example, the Gaussian elimination (or LU decomposition) method is of order O ⁡ ( n 3 ) {\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n^{3})} ({\displaystyle \operatorname {O} (n^{3})}), but the bit length of intermediate values can become exponentially long.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In mathematics, the **dot product** is an algebraic operation that takes two equal-length sequences of numbers (usually coordinate vectors), and returns a single number.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In Euclidean geometry, the **scalar product** of two vectors is the dot product of their Cartesian coordinates, and is independent from the choice of a particular Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The terms "dot product" and "scalar product" are often used interchangeably when a Cartesian coordinate system has been fixed once for all.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The scalar product being a particular inner product, the term "inner product" is also often used.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Algebraically, the dot product is the sum of the products of the corresponding entries of the two sequences of numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Geometrically, the scalar product of two vectors is the product of their lengths and the cosine of the angle between them.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] These definitions are equivalent when using Cartesian coordinates.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In modern geometry, Euclidean spaces are often defined by using vector spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In this case, the scalar product is used for defining lengths (the length of a vector is the square root of the scalar product of the vector by itself) and angles (the cosine of the angle between two vectors is the quotient of their scalar product by the product of their lengths).
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The name "dot product" is derived from the dot operator " **⋅** " that is often used to designate this operation; the alternative name "scalar product" emphasizes that the result is a scalar, rather than a vector (as with the vector product in three-dimensional space).
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The dot product may be defined algebraically or geometrically.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The geometric definition is based on the notions of angle and distance (magnitude) of vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The equivalence of these two definitions relies on having a Cartesian coordinate system for Euclidean space.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In modern presentations of Euclidean geometry, the points of space are defined in terms of their Cartesian coordinates, and Euclidean space itself is commonly identified with the real coordinate space $\mathbf {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In such a presentation, the notions of length and angle are defined by means of the dot product.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The length of a vector is defined as the square root of the dot product of the vector by itself, and the cosine of the (non oriented) angle between two vectors of length one is defined as their dot product.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] So the equivalence of the two definitions of the dot product is a part of the equivalence of the classical and the modern formulations of Euclidean geometry.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] where n is the dimension of the vector space.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] If vectors are identified with column vectors, the dot product can also be written as a matrix product $\mathbf {a} \cdot \mathbf {b} =\mathbf {a} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {b} ,$ where $\mathbf {a} {^{\mathsf {T}}}$ denotes the transpose of $\mathbf {a}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In Euclidean space, a Euclidean vector is a geometric object that possesses both a magnitude and a direction.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Its magnitude is its length, and its direction is the direction to which the arrow points.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The magnitude of a vector $\mathbf {a}$ is denoted by $\left\|\mathbf {a} \right\|$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The dot product of two Euclidean vectors $\mathbf {a}$ and $\mathbf {b}$ is defined by $\mathbf {a} \cdot \mathbf {b} =\left\|\mathbf {a} \right\|\left\|\mathbf {b} \right\|\cos \theta ,$ where $\theta$ is the angle between $\mathbf {a}$ and $\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The scalar projection (or scalar component) of a Euclidean vector $\mathbf {a}$ in the direction of a Euclidean vector $\mathbf {b}$ is given by $a_{b}=\left\|\mathbf {a} \right\|\cos \theta ,$ where $\theta$ is the angle between $\mathbf {a}$ and $\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In terms of the geometric definition of the dot product, this can be rewritten as $a_{b}=\mathbf {a} \cdot {\widehat {\mathbf {b} }},$ where ${\widehat {\mathbf {b} }}=\mathbf {b} /\left\|\mathbf {b} \right\|$ is the unit vector in the direction of $\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] These properties may be summarized by saying that the dot product is a bilinear form.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Moreover, this bilinear form is positive definite, which means that $\mathbf {a} \cdot \mathbf {a}$ is never negative, and is zero if and only if $\mathbf {a} =\mathbf {0}$ , the zero vector.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The last step in the equality can be seen from the figure.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] So the geometric dot product equals the algebraic dot product.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The dot product fulfills the following properties if $\mathbf {a}$ , $\mathbf {b}$ , $\mathbf {c}$ and $\mathbf {d}$ are real vectors and $\alpha$ , $\beta$ , $\gamma$ and $\delta$ are scalars.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] and one may say that "the dot product is associative with respect to scalar multiplication".
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Given two vectors ${\color {red}\mathbf {a} }$ and ${\color {blue}\mathbf {b} }$ separated by angle $\theta$ (see the upper image), they form a triangle with a third side ${\color {orange}\mathbf {c} }={\color {red}\mathbf {a} }-{\color {blue}\mathbf {b} }$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Let $\color {red}a$ , $\color {blue}b$ and $\color {orange}c$ denote the lengths of ${\color {red}\mathbf {a} }$ , ${\color {blue}\mathbf {b} }$ , and ${\color {orange}\mathbf {c} }$ , respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] There are two ternary operations involving dot product and cross product.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] It is the signed volume of the parallelepiped defined by the three vectors, and is isomorphic to the three-dimensional special case of the exterior product of three vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] This formula has applications in simplifying vector calculations in physics.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In physics, the dot product takes two vectors and returns a scalar quantity.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] It is also known as the "scalar product".
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The dot product of two vectors can be defined as the product of the magnitudes of the two vectors and the cosine of the angle between the two vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Thus, $\mathbf {a} \cdot \mathbf {b} =|\mathbf {a} |\,|\mathbf {b} |\cos \theta$ Alternatively, it is defined as the product of the projection of the first vector onto the second vector and the magnitude of the second vector.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] For vectors with complex entries, using the given definition of the dot product would lead to quite different properties.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] For instance, the dot product of a vector with itself could be zero without the vector being the zero vector (e.g. this would happen with the vector $\mathbf {a} =[1\ i]$ ).
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] This in turn would have consequences for notions like length and angle.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] In the case of vectors with real components, this definition is the same as in the real case.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The dot product of any vector with itself is a non-negative real number, and it is nonzero except for the zero vector.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] However, the complex dot product is sesquilinear rather than bilinear, as it is conjugate linear and not linear in $\mathbf {a}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The complex dot product leads to the notions of Hermitian forms and general inner product spaces, which are widely used in mathematics and physics.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The inner product generalizes the dot product to abstract vector spaces over a field of scalars, being either the field of real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ or the field of complex numbers $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] It is usually denoted using angular brackets by $\left\langle \mathbf {a} \,,\mathbf {b} \right\rangle$ .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The inner product of two vectors over the field of complex numbers is, in general, a complex number, and is sesquilinear instead of bilinear.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] An inner product space is a normed vector space, and the inner product of a vector with itself is real and positive-definite.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The dot product is defined for vectors that have a finite number of entries.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Thus these vectors can be regarded as discrete functions: a length- n vector u is, then, a function with domain $\{k\in \mathbb {N} :1\leq k\leq n\}$ , and $u_{i}$ is a notation for the image of i by the function/vector u .
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Inner products can have a weight function (i.e., a function which weights each term of the inner product with a value).
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] A double-dot product for matrices is the Frobenius inner product, which is analogous to the dot product on vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] Writing a matrix as a dyadic, we can define a different double-dot product (see *Dyadics § Product of dyadic and dyadic*) however it is not an inner product.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The (single-) dot product between a tensor of order n and a tensor of order m is a tensor of order $n+m-2$ (more generally, each dot reduces the order by 2), see *Tensor contraction* for details.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] The straightforward algorithm for calculating a floating-point dot product of vectors can suffer from catastrophic cancellation.
[src:linear-algebra/dot-product] To avoid this, approaches such as the Kahan summation algorithm are used.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In linear algebra, an **eigenvector** (/ˈaɪɡən-/ *EYE-gən-*) or **characteristic vector** is a (nonzero) vector that has its direction unchanged (or reversed) by a given linear transformation.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] More precisely, an eigenvector $\mathbf {v}$ of a linear transformation T is scaled by a constant factor $\lambda$ when the linear transformation is applied to it: ⁠ $T\mathbf {v} =\lambda \mathbf {v}$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The corresponding **eigenvalue**, **characteristic value**, or **characteristic root** is the multiplying factor $\lambda$ (possibly a negative or complex number).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Geometrically, vectors are multi-dimensional quantities with magnitude and direction, often pictured as arrows.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A linear transformation rotates, stretches, or shears the vectors upon which it acts.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A linear transformation's eigenvectors are those vectors that are only stretched or shrunk, with neither rotation nor shear.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The corresponding eigenvalue is the factor by which an eigenvector is stretched or shrunk.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If the eigenvalue is negative, then the eigenvector's direction is reversed.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors and eigenvalues of a linear transformation serve to characterize it, and so they play important roles in all areas where linear algebra is applied, from geology to quantum mechanics.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In particular, it is often the case that a system is represented by a linear transformation whose outputs are fed as inputs to the same transformation (feedback).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In such an application, the largest eigenvalue is of particular importance, because it governs the long-term behavior of the system after many applications of the linear transformation, and the associated eigenvector is the steady state of the system.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This relationship can be expressed as: ⁠ $A\mathbf {v} =\lambda \mathbf {v}$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Given an ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional vector space and a choice of basis, there is a direct correspondence between linear transformations from the vector space into itself and ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ square matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Hence, in a finite-dimensional vector space, it is equivalent to define eigenvalues and eigenvectors using either the language of linear transformations, or the language of matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Eigenvalues and eigenvectors feature prominently in the analysis of linear transformations.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The prefix *eigen-* is adopted from the German *eigen* (cognate with the English word *own*) for 'proper', 'characteristic', 'own'.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Originally used to study principal axes of the rotational motion of rigid bodies, eigenvalues and eigenvectors have a wide range of applications, for example in stability analysis, vibration analysis, atomic orbitals, facial recognition, and matrix diagonalization.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In essence, an eigenvector **v** of a linear transformation T is a nonzero vector that, when T is applied to it, does not change direction.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Applying T to the eigenvector only scales the eigenvector by the scalar value λ, called an eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This condition can be written as the equation $T(\mathbf {v} )=\lambda \mathbf {v} ,$ referred to as the **eigenvalue equation** or **eigenequation**.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For example, λ may be negative, in which case the eigenvector reverses direction as part of the scaling, or it may be zero, or complex.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The example here, based on the Mona Lisa, provides a simple illustration.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Each point on the painting can be represented as a vector pointing from the center of the painting to that point.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The linear transformation in this example is called a shear mapping.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Points in the top half are moved to the right, and points in the bottom half are moved to the left, proportional to how far they are from the horizontal axis that goes through the middle of the painting.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The vectors pointing to each point in the original image are therefore tilted right or left, and made longer or shorter by the transformation.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Points *along* the horizontal axis do not move at all when this transformation is applied.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, any vector that points directly to the right or left with no vertical component is an eigenvector of this transformation, because the mapping does not change its direction.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Moreover, these eigenvectors all have an eigenvalue equal to one, because the mapping does not change their length either.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Linear transformations can take many different forms, mapping vectors in a variety of vector spaces, so the eigenvectors can also take many forms.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If the linear transformation is expressed in the form of an n × n matrix A, then the eigenvalue equation for a linear transformation above can be rewritten as the matrix multiplication $A\mathbf {v} =\lambda \mathbf {v} ,$ where the eigenvector **v** is an n × 1 matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For a matrix, eigenvalues and eigenvectors can be used to decompose the matrix; for example, by diagonalizing it.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Additional animations of eigenvectors and eigenvalues in two dimensions, including symmetric transformations and transformations with complex eigenvalues, are available at Wikimedia Commons.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Eigenvalues are often introduced in the context of linear algebra or matrix theory.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Historically, however, they arose in the study of quadratic forms and differential equations.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In the 18th century, Leonhard Euler studied the rotational motion of a rigid body, and discovered the importance of the principal axes.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Joseph-Louis Lagrange realized that the principal axes are the eigenvectors of the inertia matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In the early 19th century, Augustin-Louis Cauchy saw how their work could be used to classify the quadric surfaces, and generalized it to arbitrary dimensions.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Cauchy also coined the term *racine caractéristique* (characteristic root), for what is now called *eigenvalue*; his term survives in *characteristic equation*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Later, Joseph Fourier used the work of Lagrange and Pierre-Simon Laplace to solve the heat equation by separation of variables in his 1822 treatise *The Analytic Theory of Heat (Théorie analytique de la chaleur)*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Charles-François Sturm elaborated on Fourier's ideas further, and brought them to the attention of Cauchy, who combined them with his own ideas and arrived at the fact that real symmetric matrices have real eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This was extended by Charles Hermite in 1855 to what are now called Hermitian matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Around the same time, Francesco Brioschi proved that the eigenvalues of orthogonal matrices lie on the unit circle, and Alfred Clebsch found the corresponding result for skew-symmetric matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Finally, Karl Weierstrass clarified an important aspect in the stability theory started by Laplace, by realizing that defective matrices can cause instability.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In the meantime, Joseph Liouville studied eigenvalue problems similar to those of Sturm; the discipline that grew out of their work is now called *Sturm–Liouville theory*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Schwarz studied the first eigenvalue of Laplace's equation on general domains towards the end of the 19th century, while Poincaré studied Poisson's equation a few years later.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] At the start of the 20th century, David Hilbert studied the eigenvalues of integral operators by viewing the operators as infinite matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] He was the first to use the German word *eigen*, which means "own", to denote eigenvalues and eigenvectors in 1904, though he may have been following a related usage by Hermann von Helmholtz.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For some time, the standard term in English was "proper value", but the more distinctive term "eigenvalue" is the standard today.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The first numerical algorithm for computing eigenvalues and eigenvectors appeared in 1929, when Richard von Mises published the power method.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] One of the most popular methods today, the QR algorithm, was proposed independently by John G.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Eigenvalues and eigenvectors are often introduced to students in the context of linear algebra courses focused on matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Furthermore, linear transformations over a finite-dimensional vector space can be represented using matrices, which is especially common in numerical and computational applications.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] then ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ is an **eigenvector** of the linear transformation ⁠ A ⁠ and the scale factor ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ is the **eigenvalue** corresponding to that eigenvector.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Equation (**1**) is the **eigenvalue equation** for the matrix ⁠ A ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] where ⁠ I ⁠ is the ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ identity matrix and ⁠ $\mathbf {0}$ ⁠ is the zero vector.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Equation (**2**) has a nonzero solution v if and only if the determinant of the matrix (*A* − *λI*) is zero.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Using the Leibniz formula for determinants, the left-hand side of equation (**3**) is a polynomial function of the variable λ and the degree of this polynomial is n, the order of the matrix A.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Its coefficients depend on the entries of A, except that its term of degree n is always (−1)*n**λ**n*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This polynomial is called the *characteristic polynomial* of A.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Equation (**3**) is called the *characteristic equation* or *secular equation* of A.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The characteristic polynomial of an n-by-n matrix A, being a polynomial of degree n, has at most n complex number roots, which can be found by factoring the characteristic polynomial, or numerically by root finding.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] where the complex numbers *λ*1, *λ*2, ..., *λ**n*, each of which is an eigenvalue, may repeat.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors corresponding to each eigenvalue λ can be found by solving for the components of **v** in the equation (*A* − *λI*)**v** = **0**.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If the entries of the matrix A are all real numbers, then the coefficients of the characteristic polynomial will also be real numbers, but the eigenvalues may still have nonzero imaginary parts.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The entries of the corresponding eigenvectors therefore may also have nonzero imaginary parts.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Similarly, the eigenvalues may be irrational numbers even if all the entries of A are rational numbers or even if they are all integers.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] However, if the entries of A are all algebraic numbers, which include the rationals, then the eigenvalues must also be algebraic numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The non-real roots of a real polynomial with real coefficients can be grouped into pairs of complex conjugates, namely with the two members of each pair having imaginary parts that differ only in sign and the same real part.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If the degree is odd, then by the intermediate value theorem at least one of the roots is real.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, any real matrix with odd order has at least one real eigenvalue, whereas a real matrix with even order may not have any real eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors associated with these complex eigenvalues are also complex and also appear in complex conjugate pairs.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The **spectrum** of a matrix is the list of its eigenvalues, repeated according to their multiplicities; in a shorter notation, the set of its eigenvalues with their multiplicities indicated.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] An important quantity associated with the spectrum of a matrix is the maximum absolute value of all of its eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This is known as the spectral radius of the considered matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let *λ**i* be an eigenvalue of an n-by-n matrix A.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The **algebraic multiplicity** *μ**A*(*λ**i*) of the eigenvalue is its multiplicity as a root of the characteristic polynomial, that is, the largest integer k such that (*λ**i* − *λ*)*k* evenly divides that polynomial.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Suppose a matrix A has order n and *d* ≤ *n* distinct eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The size of each eigenvalue's algebraic multiplicity is related to the dimension n as ${\begin{aligned}1&\leq \mu _{A}(\lambda _{i})\leq n,\\\mu _{A}&=\sum _{i=1}^{d}\mu _{A}\left(\lambda _{i}\right)=n.\end{aligned}}$ If *μ**A*(*λ**i*) = 1, then λi is said to be a **simple eigenvalue**.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If *μ**A*(*λ**i*) equals the geometric multiplicity of λi (denoted by *γ**A*(*λ**i*) and defined in the next section), then λi is said to be a **semisimple eigenvalue**.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Given a particular eigenvalue ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ of the ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrix ⁠ A ⁠, define the set ⁠ E ⁠ to be all vectors ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ that satisfy equation (**2**): $E=\left\{\mathbf {v$ On one hand, ⁠ E ⁠ is precisely the *kernel* or *nullspace* of the matrix ⁠ $A-\lambda I$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] On the other hand, by definition, any nonzero vector that satisfies this condition is an eigenvector of ⁠ A ⁠ associated with ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠; so ⁠ E ⁠ is the union of the zero vector with the set of all eigenvectors of ⁠ A ⁠ associated with ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The space ⁠ E ⁠ is called the **eigenspace** or **characteristic space** of ⁠ A ⁠ associated with ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In general, ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ is a complex number and the eigenvectors are complex ⁠ $n\times 1$ ⁠ matrices (column vectors).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Because every nullspace is a linear subspace of the domain, ⁠ E ⁠ is a linear subspace of ⁠ $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Because the eigenspace ⁠ E ⁠ is a linear subspace, it is closed under addition.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] That is, if two vectors ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ belong to the set ⁠ E ⁠, written ⁠ $\mathbf {u} ,\mathbf {v} \in E$ ⁠, then ⁠ $\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v} \in E$ ⁠, or equivalently ⁠ $A(\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v} )=\lambda (\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v} )$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This can be checked using the distributive property of matrix multiplication.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Similarly, because ⁠ E ⁠ is a linear subspace, it is closed under scalar multiplication.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] That is, if ⁠ $\mathbf {v} \in E$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\alpha \in \mathbb {C}$ ⁠, then ⁠ $\alpha \mathbf {v} \in E$ ⁠, or equivalently ⁠ $A(\alpha \mathbf {v} )=\lambda (\alpha \mathbf {v} )$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This can be checked by noting that multiplication of complex matrices by complex numbers is commutative.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] As long as ⁠ $\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\alpha \mathbf {v}$ ⁠ are not zero, they are also eigenvectors of ⁠ A ⁠ associated with ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The dimension of the eigenspace ⁠ E ⁠ associated with ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠, or equivalently the maximum number of linearly independent eigenvectors associated with ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠, is referred to as the eigenvalue's **geometric multiplicity** and denoted by ⁠ $\gamma _{A}(\lambda )$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Because ⁠ E ⁠ is also the nullspace of ⁠ $A-\lambda I$ ⁠, the geometric multiplicity of ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ is the dimension of the nullspace of ⁠ $A-\lambda I$ ⁠, also called the **nullity** of ⁠ $A-\lambda I$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Furthermore, an eigenvalue's geometric multiplicity cannot exceed its algebraic multiplicity.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Additionally, recall that an eigenvalue's algebraic multiplicity cannot exceed ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Proof of inequality ⁠ $\gamma _{A}(\lambda )\leq \mu _{A}(\lambda )$ ⁠: Let *B* = *A* − *λI*, where λ is a fixed complex number, and the eigenspace associated with λ is the nullspace of B.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let the dimension of that eigenspace be ⁠ $k=\gamma _{A}(\lambda )$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This means that the last k rows of the echelon form of B are zero.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Thus, there is an invertible matrix E coming from Gauss-Jordan reduction, such that $EB={\begin{bmatrix}*&*\\\mathbf {0} _{k\times (n-k)}&\mathbf {0} _{k\times k}\end{bmatrix}}.$ Therefore the last k rows of *EB* − *tE* are (−*t*) times the last k rows of E.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore the polynomial tk evenly divides the polynomial det(*EB* − *tE*), because of basic properties of determinants (homogeneity).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] On the other hand, det(*EB* − *tE*) = det *E* det(*B* − *tI*) = *pA*(*t* + *λ*) det *E*, so (*t* − *λ*)*k* divides *pA*(*t*), and so the algebraic multiplicity of λ is at least ⁠ k ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Suppose A has *d* ≤ *n* distinct eigenvalues *λ*1, ..., *λ**d*, where the geometric multiplicity of λi is *γA*(*λi*).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The total geometric multiplicity of A, $\gamma _{A}=\sum _{i=1}^{d}\gamma _{A}(\lambda _{i}),$ is the dimension of the sum of all the eigenspaces of A's eigenvalues, or equivalently the maximum number of linearly independent eigenvectors of A.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] By construction, ⁠ $d\leq \gamma _{A}\leq n$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let A be an arbitrary n × n matrix of complex numbers with eigenvalues *λ*1, ..., *λn*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Each eigenvalue appears *μA*(*λi*) times in this list, where *μA*(*λi*) is the eigenvalue's algebraic multiplicity.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Many disciplines traditionally represent vectors as matrices with a single column rather than as matrices with a single row.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In this formulation, the defining equation is $\mathbf {u} A=\kappa \mathbf {u} ,$ where κ is a scalar and **u** is a 1 × n matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Any row vector **u** satisfying this equation is called a '**left eigenvector**' of A, and κ is still called its associated eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Comparing this equation to equation (**1**), it follows immediately that a left eigenvector of ⁠ A ⁠ is the same as the transpose of a right eigenvector of ⁠ $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ ⁠, with the same eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Furthermore, since the characteristic polynomial of ⁠ $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ ⁠ is the same as the characteristic polynomial of ⁠ A ⁠, the left and right eigenvectors of ⁠ A ⁠ are associated with the same eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A matrix has the same eigenvalues as its transpose, as can be directly seen as follows.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Assume ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ is an eigenvalue of an ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrix ⁠ A ⁠ with eigenvector ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Thus, the columns of ⁠ $(A-\lambda I)$ ⁠ are linearly dependent.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Equivalently, the rank of the matrix is less than ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] But as column rank = row rank, the rows are also linearly dependent.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Moreover, ⁠ $y^{\mathsf {T}}$ ⁠ is not the zero vector; so ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ is also an eigenvalue of ⁠ $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Furthermore, this argument shows that the eigenvalues of A and $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ have the same geometric multiplicity (since column nullity = row nullity).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Suppose the eigenvectors of A form a basis of ⁠ $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ ⁠, or equivalently A has n linearly independent eigenvectors **v**1, **v**2, ..., **v***n* (with associated eigenvalues *λ*1, *λ*2, ..., *λ**n*).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors need not be orthogonal to one another, and the eigenvalues need not be distinct.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] With this in mind, define the diagonal matrix Λ where each diagonal element Λii is the eigenvalue associated with the ith column of Q.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Then $AQ=Q\varLambda .$ Because the columns of Q are linearly independent, Q is invertible.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This is called the eigendecomposition; it is a similarity transformation.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Such a matrix A is said to be **similar** to the diagonal matrix Λ, or *diagonalizable*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The matrix Q is the change of basis matrix of the similarity transformation.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Essentially, the matrices A and Λ represent the same linear transformation expressed in two different bases.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors are used as the basis when representing the linear transformation as Λ.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Conversely, suppose a matrix A is diagonalizable.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let P be a non-singular square matrix such that *P*−1*AP* is some diagonal matrix D.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Left multiplying both by P yields *AP* = *PD*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Each column of P must therefore be an eigenvector of A whose eigenvalue is the corresponding diagonal element of D.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Since the columns of P must be linearly independent for P to be invertible, there exist n linearly independent eigenvectors of A.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In conclusion, the eigenvectors of ⁠ A ⁠ form a basis of ⁠ $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ ⁠ if and only if ⁠ A ⁠ is diagonalizable.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A matrix that is not diagonalizable is said to be *defective*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For defective matrices, the notion of eigenvectors generalizes to generalized eigenvectors and the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues generalizes to the Jordan normal form.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Over an algebraically closed field, any matrix A has a Jordan normal form and therefore admits a basis of generalized eigenvectors and a decomposition into generalized eigenspaces.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In the Hermitian case, eigenvalues can be given a variational characterization.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The largest eigenvalue of H is the maximum value of the quadratic form **x**T*H***x**/**x**T**x**.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A value of **x** that realizes that maximum is an eigenvector.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Consider the matrix $A={\begin{bmatrix}2&1\\1&2\end{bmatrix}}.$ The figure on the right shows the effect of this transformation on point coordinates in the plane.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors v of this transformation satisfy equation (**1**), and the values of λ for which the determinant of the matrix (*A* − *λI*) equals zero are the eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, $\mathbf {v} _{\lambda =1}={\begin{bmatrix}v_{1}\\-v_{1}\end{bmatrix}}={\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}}$ is an eigenvector of A corresponding to *λ* = 1, as is any scalar multiple of this vector.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, $\mathbf {v} _{\lambda =3}={\begin{bmatrix}v_{1}\\v_{1}\end{bmatrix}}={\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}}$ is an eigenvector of A corresponding to *λ* = 3, as is any scalar multiple of this vector.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Thus, the vectors **v***λ*=1 and **v***λ*=3 are eigenvectors of A associated with the eigenvalues *λ* = 1 and *λ* = 3, respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The roots of the characteristic polynomial are 2, 1, and 11, which are the only three eigenvalues of A.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] These eigenvalues correspond to the eigenvectors [1 0 0]T, [0 −2 1]T, and [0 1 2]T, or any nonzero multiple thereof.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This matrix shifts the coordinates of the vector up by one position and moves the first coordinate to the bottom.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For the real eigenvalue *λ*1 = 1, any vector with three equal nonzero entries is an eigenvector.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, the other two eigenvectors of A are complex and are **v***λ*2 = [1 *λ*2 *λ*3]T and **v***λ*3 = [1 *λ*3 *λ*2]T with eigenvalues *λ*2 and *λ*3, respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Matrices with entries only along the main diagonal are called *diagonal matrices*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix are the diagonal elements themselves.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] These roots are the diagonal elements as well as the eigenvalues of A.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Each diagonal element corresponds to an eigenvector whose only nonzero component is in the same row as that diagonal element.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A matrix whose elements above the main diagonal are all zero is called a *lower triangular matrix*, while a matrix whose elements below the main diagonal are all zero is called an *upper triangular matrix*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] As with diagonal matrices, the eigenvalues of triangular matrices are the elements of the main diagonal.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The roots of this polynomial, and hence the eigenvalues, are 2 and 3.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The **algebraic multiplicity** of each eigenvalue is 2; in other words they are both double roots.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The sum of the algebraic multiplicities of all distinct eigenvalues is *μ**A* = 4 = *n*, the order of the characteristic polynomial and the dimension of A.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] On the other hand, the **geometric multiplicity** of the eigenvalue 2 is only 1, because its eigenspace is spanned by just one vector [0 1 −1 1]T and is therefore 1-dimensional.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Similarly, the geometric multiplicity of the eigenvalue 3 is 1 because its eigenspace is spanned by just one vector [0 0 0 1]T.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The total geometric multiplicity *γ**A* is 2, which is the smallest it could be for a matrix with two distinct eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Geometric multiplicities are defined in a later section.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This identity also extends to diagonalizable matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] It has been discovered in and rediscovered many times in the literature (see, e.g., ).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The definitions of eigenvalue and eigenvectors of a linear transformation T remains valid even if the underlying vector space is an infinite-dimensional Hilbert or Banach space.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A widely used class of linear transformations acting on infinite-dimensional spaces are the differential operators on function spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let D be a linear differential operator on the space $C^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} )$ of infinitely differentiable real functions of a real argument t.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvalue equation for D is the differential equation $Df(t)=\lambda f(t)$ The functions that satisfy this equation are eigenvectors of D and are commonly called '**eigenfunctions**'.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Consider the derivative operator ${\tfrac {d}{dt}}$ with eigenvalue equation ${\frac {d}{dt}}f(t)=\lambda f(t).$ This differential equation can be solved by multiplying both sides by *dt*/*f*(*t*) and integrating.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Its solution, the exponential function $f(t)=f(0)e^{\lambda t},$ is the eigenfunction of the derivative operator.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In this case the eigenfunction is itself a function of its associated eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In particular, for *λ* = 0 the eigenfunction *f*(*t*) is a constant.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The concept of eigenvalues and eigenvectors extends naturally to arbitrary linear transformations on arbitrary vector spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This equation is called the eigenvalue equation for T, and the scalar λ is the **eigenvalue** of T corresponding to the eigenvector **v**.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] *T*(**v**) is the result of applying the transformation T to the vector **v**, while *λ***v** is the product of the scalar λ with **v**.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Given an eigenvalue λ, consider the set $E=\left\{\mathbf {v} :T(\mathbf {v} )=\lambda \mathbf {v} \right\},$ which is the union of the zero vector with the set of all eigenvectors associated with λ.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] E is called the '**eigenspace**' or '**characteristic space**' of T associated with λ.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] It is the kernel of the linear transformation *T* − *λI*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenspace E associated with λ is therefore a linear subspace of V.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If that subspace has dimension 1, it is sometimes called an '**eigenline**'.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The '**geometric multiplicity**' *γ**T*(*λ*) of an eigenvalue λ is the dimension of the eigenspace associated with λ, i.e., the maximum number of linearly independent eigenvectors associated with that eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] By the definition of eigenvalues and eigenvectors, *γ**T*(*λ*) ≥ 1 because every eigenvalue has at least one eigenvector.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenspaces of T always form a direct sum.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] As a consequence, eigenvectors of *different* eigenvalues are always linearly independent.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, the sum of the dimensions of the eigenspaces cannot exceed the dimension n of the vector space on which T operates, and there cannot be more than n distinct eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Any subspace spanned by eigenvectors of T is an invariant subspace of T, and the restriction of T to such a subspace is diagonalizable.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] When T admits an eigenbasis, T is diagonalizable.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If λ is an eigenvalue of T, then the operator (*T* − *λI*) is not one-to-one, and therefore its inverse (*T* − *λI*)−1 does not exist.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The converse is true for finite-dimensional vector spaces, but not for infinite-dimensional vector spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In general, the operator (*T* − *λI*) may not have an inverse even if λ is not an eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For this reason, in functional analysis eigenvalues can be generalized to the spectrum of a linear operator T as the set of all scalars λ for which the operator (*T* − *λI*) has no bounded inverse.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The spectrum of an operator always contains all its eigenvalues but is not limited to them.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] One can generalize the algebraic object that is acting on the vector space, replacing a single operator acting on a vector space with an algebra representation – an associative algebra acting on a module.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The study of such actions is the field of representation theory.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The representation-theoretical concept of weight is an analog of eigenvalues, while *weight vectors* and *weight spaces* are the analogs of eigenvectors and eigenspaces, respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Hecke eigensheaf is a tensor-multiple of itself and is considered in Langlands correspondence.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The calculation of eigenvalues and eigenvectors is a topic where theory, as presented in elementary linear algebra textbooks, is often very far from practice.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The classical method is to first find the eigenvalues, and then calculate the eigenvectors for each eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] It is in several ways poorly suited for non-exact arithmetics such as floating-point.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvalues of a matrix A can be determined by finding the roots of the characteristic polynomial.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This is easy for 2 × 2 matrices, but the difficulty increases rapidly with the size of the matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In theory, the coefficients of the characteristic polynomial can be computed exactly, since they are sums of products of matrix elements; and there are algorithms that can find all the roots of a polynomial of arbitrary degree to any required accuracy.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] However, this approach is not viable in practice because the coefficients would be contaminated by unavoidable round-off errors, and the roots of a polynomial can be an extremely sensitive function of the coefficients (as exemplified by Wilkinson's polynomial).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Even for matrices whose elements are integers the calculation becomes nontrivial, because the sums are very long; the constant term is the determinant, which for an n × n matrix is a sum of *n*! different products.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Explicit algebraic formulas for the roots of a polynomial exist only if the degree n is 4 or less.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] According to the Abel–Ruffini theorem there is no general, explicit and exact algebraic formula for the roots of a polynomial with degree 5 or more.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Even the exact formula for the roots of a degree 3 polynomial is numerically impractical.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Once the (exact) value of an eigenvalue is known, the corresponding eigenvectors can be found by finding nonzero solutions of the eigenvalue equation, that becomes a system of linear equations with known coefficients.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Both equations reduce to the single linear equation *y* = 2*x*.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Therefore, any vector of the form [*a* 2*a*]T, for any nonzero real number a, is an eigenvector of A with eigenvalue *λ* = 6.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The matrix A above has another eigenvalue *λ* = 1.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A similar calculation shows that the corresponding eigenvectors are the nonzero solutions of 3*x* + *y* = 0, that is, any vector of the form [*b* −3*b*]T, for any nonzero real number b.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The converse approach, of first seeking the eigenvectors and then determining each eigenvalue from its eigenvector, turns out to be far more tractable for computers.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The easiest algorithm here consists of picking an arbitrary starting vector and then repeatedly multiplying it with the matrix (optionally normalizing the vector to keep its elements of reasonable size); this makes the vector converge towards an eigenvector.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A variation is to instead multiply the vector by (*A* − *μI*)−1; this causes it to converge to an eigenvector of the eigenvalue closest to $\mu \in \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If **v** is (a good approximation of) an eigenvector of A, then the corresponding eigenvalue can be computed as $\lambda ={\frac {\mathbf {v} ^{*}A\mathbf {v} }{\mathbf {v} ^{*}\mathbf {v} }}$ where **v**∗ denotes the conjugate transpose of **v**.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Efficient, accurate methods to compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors of arbitrary matrices were not known until the QR algorithm was designed in 1961.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Combining the Householder transformation with the LU decomposition results in an algorithm with better convergence than the QR algorithm.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] For large Hermitian sparse matrices, the Lanczos algorithm is one example of an efficient iterative method to compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors, among several other possibilities.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Most numeric methods that compute the eigenvalues of a matrix also determine a set of corresponding eigenvectors as a by-product of the computation, although sometimes implementors choose to discard the eigenvector information as soon as it is no longer needed.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Eigenvectors and eigenvalues can be useful for understanding linear transformations of geometric shapes.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The following table presents some example transformations in the plane along with their 2 × 2 matrices, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The characteristic equation for a rotation is a quadratic equation with discriminant *D* = −4(sin *θ*)2, which is a negative number whenever θ is not an integer multiple of π (180°).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Therefore, except for these special cases, the two eigenvalues are complex numbers, cos *θ* ± *i*sin *θ*; and all eigenvectors have non-real entries.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Indeed, except for those special cases, a rotation changes the direction of every nonzero vector in the plane.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A linear transformation that takes a square to a rectangle of the same area (a squeeze mapping) has reciprocal eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigendecomposition of a symmetric positive semidefinite (PSD) matrix yields an orthogonal basis of eigenvectors, each of which has a nonnegative eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The orthogonal decomposition of a PSD matrix is used in multivariate analysis, where the sample covariance matrices are PSD.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This orthogonal decomposition is called principal component analysis (PCA) in statistics.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] PCA studies linear relations among variables.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] PCA is performed on the covariance matrix or the correlation matrix (in which each variable is scaled to have its sample variance equal to one).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] For the covariance or correlation matrix, the eigenvectors correspond to principal components and the eigenvalues to the variance explained by the principal components.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Principal component analysis of the correlation matrix provides an orthogonal basis for the space of the observed data: In this basis, the largest eigenvalues correspond to the principal components that are associated with most of the covariability among a number of observed data.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Principal component analysis is used as a means of dimensionality reduction in the study of large data sets, such as those encountered in bioinformatics.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In Q methodology, the eigenvalues of the correlation matrix determine the Q-methodologist's judgment of *practical* significance (which differs from the statistical significance of hypothesis testing; cf. criteria for determining the number of factors).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] More generally, principal component analysis can be used as a method of factor analysis in structural equation modeling.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The kth principal eigenvector of a graph is defined as either the eigenvector corresponding to the kth largest or kth smallest eigenvalue of the Laplacian.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The first principal eigenvector of the graph is also referred to merely as the principal eigenvector.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The principal eigenvector is used to measure the centrality of its vertices.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] An example is Google's PageRank algorithm.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The principal eigenvector of a modified adjacency matrix of the World Wide Web graph gives the page ranks as its components.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This vector corresponds to the stationary distribution of the Markov chain represented by the row-normalized adjacency matrix; however, the adjacency matrix must first be modified to ensure a stationary distribution exists.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The second smallest eigenvector can be used to partition the graph into clusters, via spectral clustering.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Other methods are also available for clustering.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A Markov chain is represented by a matrix whose entries are the transition probabilities between states of a system.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In particular the entries are non-negative, and every row of the matrix sums to one, being the sum of probabilities of transitions from one state to some other state of the system.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The Perron–Frobenius theorem gives sufficient conditions for a Markov chain to have a unique dominant eigenvalue, which governs the convergence of the system to a steady state.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Eigenvalue problems occur naturally in the vibration analysis of mechanical structures with many degrees of freedom.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvalues are the natural frequencies (or '**eigenfrequencies**') of vibration, and the eigenvectors are the shapes of these vibrational modes.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] That is, acceleration is proportional to position (i.e., we expect x to be sinusoidal in time).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In n dimensions, m becomes a mass matrix and k a stiffness matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Admissible solutions are then a linear combination of solutions to the generalized eigenvalue problem $kx=\omega ^{2}mx$ where *ω*2 is the eigenvalue and ω is the (imaginary) angular frequency.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The principal vibration modes are different from the principal compliance modes, which are the eigenvectors of k alone.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Furthermore, damped vibration, governed by $m{\ddot {x}}+c{\dot {x}}+kx=0$ leads to a so-called quadratic eigenvalue problem, $\left(\omega ^{2}m+\omega c+k\right)x=0.$ This can be reduced to a generalized eigenvalue problem by algebraic manipulation at the cost of solving a larger system.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The orthogonality properties of the eigenvectors allows decoupling of the differential equations so that the system can be represented as linear summation of the eigenvectors.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvalue problem of complex structures is often solved using finite element analysis, but neatly generalize the solution to scalar-valued vibration problems.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In mechanics, the eigenvectors of the moment of inertia tensor define the principal axes of a rigid body.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The tensor of moment of inertia is a key quantity required to determine the rotation of a rigid body around its center of mass.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In solid mechanics, the stress tensor is symmetric and so can be decomposed into a diagonal tensor with the eigenvalues on the diagonal and eigenvectors as a basis.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Because it is diagonal, in this orientation, the stress tensor has no shear components; the components it does have are the principal components.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] However, in the case where one is interested only in the bound state solutions of the Schrödinger equation, one looks for ψE within the space of square integrable functions.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Since this space is a Hilbert space with a well-defined scalar product, one can introduce a basis set in which ψE and H can be represented as a one-dimensional array (i.e., a vector) and a matrix respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This allows one to represent the Schrödinger equation in a matrix form.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The bra–ket notation is often used in this context.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A vector, which represents a state of the system, in the Hilbert space of square integrable functions is represented by |Ψ*E*⟩.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In this notation, the Schrödinger equation is: $H|\Psi _{E}\rangle =E|\Psi _{E}\rangle$ where |Ψ*E*⟩ is an '**eigenstate**' of H, and E represents the eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] H is an observable self-adjoint operator, the infinite-dimensional analog of Hermitian matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] As in the matrix case, in the equation above *H*|Ψ*E*⟩ is understood to be the vector obtained by application of the transformation H to |Ψ*E*⟩.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Light, acoustic waves, and microwaves are randomly scattered numerous times when traversing a static disordered system.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Even though multiple scattering repeatedly randomizes the waves, ultimately coherent wave transport through the system is a deterministic process which can be described by a field transmission matrix **t**.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvectors of the transmission operator **t**†**t** form a set of disorder-specific input wavefronts which enable waves to couple into the disordered system's eigenchannels: the independent pathways waves can travel through the system.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvalues, τ, of **t**†**t** correspond to the intensity transmittance associated with each eigenchannel.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] One of the remarkable properties of the transmission operator of diffusive systems is their bimodal eigenvalue distribution with *τ*max = 1 and *τ*min = 0.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Furthermore, one of the striking properties of open eigenchannels, beyond the perfect transmittance, is the statistically robust spatial profile of the eigenchannels.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In quantum mechanics, and in particular in atomic and molecular physics, within the Hartree–Fock theory, the atomic and molecular orbitals can be defined by the eigenvectors of the Fock operator.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The corresponding eigenvalues are interpreted as ionization potentials via Koopmans' theorem.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In this case, the term eigenvector is used in a somewhat more general meaning, since the Fock operator is explicitly dependent on the orbitals and their eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Thus, if one wants to underline this aspect, one speaks of nonlinear eigenvalue problems.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Such equations are usually solved by an iteration procedure, called in this case self-consistent field method.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In quantum chemistry, one often represents the Hartree–Fock equation in a non-orthogonal basis set.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This particular representation is a generalized eigenvalue problem called Roothaan equations.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In geology, especially in the study of glacial till, eigenvectors and eigenvalues are used as a method by which a mass of information of a clast's fabric can be summarized in a 3-D space by six numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In the field, a geologist may collect such data for hundreds or thousands of clasts in a soil sample, which can be compared graphically or as a stereographic projection.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Graphically, many geologists use a Tri-Plot (Sneed and Folk) diagram,.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A stereographic projection projects 3-dimensional spaces onto a two-dimensional plane.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A type of stereographic projection is Wulff Net, which is commonly used in crystallography to create stereograms.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The output for the orientation tensor is in the three orthogonal (perpendicular) axes of space.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The three eigenvectors are ordered **v**1, **v**2, **v**3 by their eigenvalues *E*1 ≥ *E*2 ≥ *E*3; **v**1 then is the primary orientation/dip of clast, **v**2 is the secondary and **v**3 is the tertiary, in terms of strength.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The clast orientation is defined as the direction of the eigenvector, on a compass rose of 360°.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Dip is measured as the eigenvalue, the modulus of the tensor: this is valued from 0° (no dip) to 90° (vertical).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The relative values of *E*1, *E*2, and *E*3 are dictated by the nature of the sediment's fabric.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If *E*1 = *E*2 = *E*3, the fabric is said to be isotropic.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If *E*1 = *E*2 > *E*3, the fabric is said to be planar.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If *E*1 > *E*2 > *E*3, the fabric is said to be linear.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The basic reproduction number (*R*0) is a fundamental number in the study of how infectious diseases spread.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If one infectious person is put into a population of completely susceptible people, then *R*0 is the average number of people that one typical infectious person will infect.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The generation time of an infection is the time, tG, from one person becoming infected to the next person becoming infected.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In a heterogeneous population, the next generation matrix defines how many people in the population will become infected after time tG has passed.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The value *R*0 is then the largest eigenvalue of the next generation matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In image processing, processed images of faces can be seen as vectors whose components are the brightnesses of each pixel.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The dimension of this vector space is the number of pixels.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvectors of the covariance matrix associated with a large set of normalized pictures of faces are called **eigenfaces**; this is an example of principal component analysis.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] They are very useful for expressing any face image as a linear combination of some of them.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In the facial recognition branch of biometrics, eigenfaces provide a means of applying data compression to faces for identification purposes.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Research related to eigen vision systems determining hand gestures has also been made.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Similar to this concept, **eigenvoices** represent the general direction of variability in human pronunciations of a particular utterance, such as a word in a language.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Based on a linear combination of such eigenvoices, a new voice pronunciation of the word can be constructed.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] These concepts have been found useful in automatic speech recognition systems for speaker adaptation.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p03] A variation is to instead multiply the vector by (*A* − *μI*)−1; this causes it to converge to an eigenvector of the eigenvalue closest to μ ∈ C {\displaystyle \mu \in \mathbb {C} } ({\displaystyle \mu \in \mathbb {C} }).
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p03] Admissible solutions are then a linear combination of solutions to the generalized eigenvalue problem k x = ω 2 m x {\displaystyle kx=\omega ^{2}mx} ({\displaystyle kx=\omega ^{2}mx}) where *ω*2 is the eigenvalue and ω is the (imaginary) angular frequency.
[src:linear-algebra/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p03] In this notation, the Schrödinger equation is: H | Ψ E ⟩ = E | Ψ E ⟩ {\displaystyle H|\Psi _{E}\rangle =E|\Psi _{E}\rangle } ({\displaystyle H|\Psi _{E}\rangle =E|\Psi _{E}\rangle }) where |Ψ*E*⟩ is an '**eigenstate**' of H, and E represents the eigenvalue.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In mathematics, **Gaussian elimination**, also known as **row reduction**, is an algorithm for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] It consists of a sequence of row-wise operations performed on the corresponding matrix of coefficients.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] This method can also be used to compute the rank of a matrix, the determinant of a square matrix, and the inverse of an invertible matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The method is named after Carl Friedrich Gauss (1777–1855).
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] To perform row reduction on a matrix, one uses a sequence of elementary row operations to modify the matrix until the lower left-hand corner of the matrix is filled with zeros, as much as possible.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] This final form is unique; in other words, it is independent of the sequence of row operations used.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Using row operations to convert a matrix into reduced row echelon form is sometimes called **Gauss–Jordan elimination**.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In this case, the term *Gaussian elimination* refers to the process until it has reached its upper triangular, (unreduced) row echelon form.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] For computational reasons, when solving systems of linear equations, it is sometimes preferable to stop row operations before the matrix is completely reduced.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The process of row reduction makes use of elementary row operations, and can be divided into two parts.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The first part (sometimes called forward elimination) reduces a given system to row echelon form, from which one can tell whether there are no solutions, a unique solution, or infinitely many solutions.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The second part (sometimes called back substitution) continues to use row operations until the solution is found; in other words, it puts the matrix into reduced row echelon form.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Another point of view, which turns out to be very useful to analyze the algorithm, is that row reduction produces a matrix decomposition of the original matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The elementary row operations may be viewed as the multiplication on the left of the original matrix by elementary matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Alternatively, a sequence of elementary operations that reduces a single row may be viewed as multiplication by a Frobenius matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Then the first part of the algorithm computes an LU decomposition, while the second part writes the original matrix as the product of a uniquely determined invertible matrix and a uniquely determined reduced row echelon matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Adding a scalar multiple of one row to another.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] If the matrix is associated to a system of linear equations, then these operations do not change the solution set.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Therefore, if one's goal is to solve a system of linear equations, then using these row operations could make the problem easier.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] For each row in a matrix, if the row does not consist of only zeros, then the leftmost nonzero entry is called the *leading entry* (or *pivot*) of that row.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] If two leading entries are in the same column, then a row operation of type 3 can be used to make one of those entries zero.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Then by using the row swapping operation, one can always order the rows so that for every non-zero row, the leading entry is to the right of the leading entry of the row above.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] If this is the case, the matrix is said to be in *row echelon form*.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In this form, the lower left part of the matrix contains only zeros, and all of the zero rows are below the non-zero rows.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The word "echelon" is used here because one can roughly think of the rows being ranked by their size, with the largest being at the top and the smallest being at the bottom.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] It is in echelon form because the zero row is at the bottom and the leading entry of the second row (in the third column) is to the right of the leading entry of the first row (in the second column).
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The table below is the row reduction process applied simultaneously to the system of equations and its associated augmented matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In practice, one does not usually deal with the systems in terms of equations, but instead makes use of the augmented matrix, which is more suitable for computer manipulations.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The row reduction procedure may be summarized as follows: eliminate x from all equations below *L*1, and then eliminate y from all equations below *L*2.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] This will put the system into triangular form.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Then, using back-substitution, each unknown can be solved for.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The second column describes which row operations have just been performed.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] For the first step, x is eliminated from *L*2 by adding ⁠3/2⁠*L*1 to *L*2.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Next, x is eliminated from *L*3 by adding *L*1 to *L*3.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Once y is also eliminated from the third row, the result is a system of linear equations in triangular form, and so the first part of the algorithm is complete.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] From a computational point of view, it is faster to solve the variables in reverse order, a process known as back-substitution.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In particular, there is a unique solution to the original system of equations in this case.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Instead of stopping once the matrix is in row echelon form, one could continue until the matrix is in *reduced* row echelon form, as it is done in the table.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The process of row reducing until the matrix is reduced is sometimes referred to as Gauss–Jordan elimination, to distinguish it from stopping after reaching echelon form.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The method of Gaussian elimination appears – albeit without proof – in the Chinese mathematical text Chapter Eight: *Rectangular Arrays* of *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art*.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Its use is illustrated in eighteen problems, with two to five equations.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The first reference to the book by this title is dated to 179 AD, but parts of it were written as early as approximately 150 BC.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] It was commented on by Liu Hui in the 3rd century.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] According to Grcar solution of linear equations by elimination was invented independently in several cultures in Eurasia starting from antiquity and in Europe definite examples of procedure were published already by late Renaissance (in 1550's).
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] It is quite possible that already then the procedure was considered by mathematicians elementary and in no need to explanation for professionals, so we may never learn its detailed history except that by then it was practiced in at least several places in Europe.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The method in Europe stems from the notes of Isaac Newton.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In 1669–1670, Newton wrote that all the algebra books known to him lacked a lesson for solving simultaneous equations, which Newton then supplied.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Cambridge University eventually published the notes as *Arithmetica Universalis* in 1707 long after Newton had left academic life.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The notes were widely imitated, which made (what is now called) Gaussian elimination a standard lesson in algebra textbooks by the end of the 18th century.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Carl Friedrich Gauss in 1810 devised a notation for symmetric elimination that was adopted in the 19th century by professional hand computers to solve the normal equations of least-squares problems.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The algorithm that is taught in high school was named for Gauss only in the 1950s as a result of confusion over the history of the subject.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Some authors use the term *Gaussian elimination* to refer only to the procedure until the matrix is in echelon form, and use the term Gauss–Jordan elimination to refer to the procedure which ends in reduced echelon form.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The name is used because it is a variation of Gaussian elimination as described by Wilhelm Jordan in 1888.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] However, the method also appears in an article by Clasen published in the same year.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Jordan and Clasen probably discovered Gauss–Jordan elimination independently.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Historically, the first application of the row reduction method is for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Below are some other important applications of the algorithm.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] If Gaussian elimination applied to a square matrix A produces a row echelon matrix B, let d be the product of the scalars by which the determinant has been multiplied, using the above rules.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Even on the fastest computers, these two methods are impractical or almost impracticable for *n* above 20.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] A variant of Gaussian elimination called **Gauss–Jordan elimination** can be used for finding the inverse of a matrix, if it exists.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] If *A* is an *n* × *n* square matrix, then one can use row reduction to compute its inverse matrix, if it exists.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] First, the *n* × *n* identity matrix is augmented to the right of *A*, forming an *n* × 2*n* block matrix [*A* | *I*].
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Now through application of elementary row operations, find the reduced echelon form of this *n* × 2*n* matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The matrix *A* is invertible if and only if it can be reduced to the identity matrix *I*; in this case the right block of the final matrix is *A*−1.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] If the algorithm is unable to reduce the left block to *I*, then *A* is not invertible.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] One can think of each row operation as the left product by an elementary matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] On the right, we see on the right that the product of these elementary matrices is *B* (since *B* = *BI*).
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Meanwhile, on the left, we see that the effect of left multiplying the product of these matrices into *A* yields the identity matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Therefore *B* = *A*−1, the inverse desired.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] This procedure for finding the inverse works for square matrices of any size.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The Gaussian elimination algorithm can be applied to any *m* × *n* matrix A.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] All of this applies also to the reduced row echelon form, which is a particular row echelon format.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The number of arithmetic operations required to perform row reduction is one way of measuring the algorithm's computational efficiency.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Thus it has a *arithmetic complexity* (time complexity, where each arithmetic operation takes one unit of time, independently of the size of the inputs) of O(*n*3).
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] This complexity is a good measure of the time needed for the whole computation when the time for each arithmetic operation is approximately constant.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] This is the case when the coefficients are represented by floating-point numbers or when they belong to a finite field.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] If the coefficients are integers or rational numbers exactly represented, the intermediate entries can grow exponentially large, so the bit complexity is exponential.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] However, the Bareiss algorithm is a variant of Gaussian elimination that avoids this exponential growth of the intermediate entries; with the same arithmetic complexity of O(*n*3), it has a bit complexity of O(*n*5), and has therefore a strongly-polynomial time complexity.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Gaussian elimination and its variants can be used on computers for systems with thousands of equations and unknowns.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] However, the cost becomes prohibitive for systems with millions of equations.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] These large systems are generally solved using iterative methods.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Specific methods exist for systems whose coefficients follow a regular pattern (see System of linear equations).
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The first strongly-polynomial time algorithm for Gaussian elimination was published by Jack Edmonds in 1967.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Independently, and almost simultaneously, Erwin Bareiss discovered another algorithm, based on the following remark, which applies to a division-free variant of Gaussian elimination.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In standard Gaussian elimination, one subtracts from each row $R_{i}$ below the pivot row $R_{k}$ a multiple of $R_{k}$ by $r_{i,k}/r_{k,k},$ where $r_{i,k}$ and $r_{k,k}$ are the entries in the pivot column of $R_{i}$ and $R_{k},$ respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Bareiss variant consists, instead, of replacing $R_{i}$ with ${\textstyle {\frac {r_{k,k}R_{i}-r_{i,k}R_{k}}{r_{k-1,k-1}}}.}$ This produces a row echelon form that has the same zero entries as with the standard Gaussian elimination.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Bareiss' main remark is that each matrix entry generated by this variant is the determinant of a submatrix of the original matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In particular, if one starts with integer entries, the divisions occurring in the algorithm are exact divisions resulting in integers.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Therefore, all intermediate entries and final entries are integers.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Moreover, Hadamard's inequality provides an upper bound on the absolute values of the intermediate and final entries, and thus a bit complexity of ${\tilde {O}}(n^{5}),$ using soft O notation.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Moreover, as an upper bound on the size of final entries is known, a complexity ${\tilde {O}}(n^{4})$ can be obtained with modular computation followed either by Chinese remaindering or Hensel lifting.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] One possible problem is numerical instability, caused by the possibility of dividing by very small numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] If, for example, the leading coefficient of one of the rows is very close to zero, then to row-reduce the matrix, one would need to divide by that number.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] This means that any error which existed for the number that was close to zero would be amplified.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Gaussian elimination is numerically stable for diagonally dominant or positive-definite matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] For general matrices, Gaussian elimination is usually considered to be stable, when using partial pivoting, even though there are examples of stable matrices for which it is unstable.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Gaussian elimination can be performed over any field, not just the real numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Buchberger's algorithm is a generalization of Gaussian elimination to systems of polynomial equations.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] This generalization depends heavily on the notion of a monomial order.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The choice of an ordering on the variables is already implicit in Gaussian elimination, manifesting as the choice to work from left to right when selecting pivot positions.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Computing the rank of a tensor of order greater than 2 is NP-hard.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Therefore, if P ≠ NP, there cannot be a polynomial time analog of Gaussian elimination for higher-order tensors (matrices are array representations of order-2 tensors).
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] As explained above, Gaussian elimination transforms a given *m* × *n* matrix A into a matrix in row-echelon form.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In the following pseudocode, `A[i, j]` denotes the entry of the matrix A in row i and column j with the indices starting from 1.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] The transformation is performed *in place*, meaning that the original matrix is lost for being eventually replaced by its row-echelon form.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] This algorithm differs slightly from the one discussed earlier, by choosing a pivot with largest absolute value.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Such a *partial pivoting* may be required if, at the pivot place, the entry of the matrix is zero.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] In any case, choosing the largest possible absolute value of the pivot improves the numerical stability of the algorithm, when floating point is used for representing numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/gaussian-elimination] Upon completion of this procedure the matrix will be in row echelon form and the corresponding system may be solved by back substitution.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] and their representations in vector spaces and through matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is central to almost all areas of mathematics.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For instance, linear algebra is fundamental in modern presentations of geometry, including for defining basic objects such as lines, planes and rotations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Also, functional analysis, a branch of mathematical analysis, may be viewed as the application of linear algebra to function spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is also used in most sciences and fields of engineering because it allows modeling many natural phenomena, and computing efficiently with such models.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For nonlinear systems, which cannot be modeled with linear algebra, it is often used for dealing with first-order approximations, using the fact that the differential of a multivariate function at a point is the linear map that best approximates the function near that point.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The procedure (using counting rods) for solving simultaneous linear equations now called Gaussian elimination appears in the ancient Chinese mathematical text Chapter Eight: *Rectangular Arrays* of *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Systems of linear equations arose in Europe with the introduction in 1637 by René Descartes of coordinates in geometry.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In fact, in this new geometry, now called Cartesian geometry, lines and planes are represented by linear equations, and computing their intersections amounts to solving systems of linear equations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The first systematic methods for solving linear systems used determinants and were first considered by Leibniz in 1693.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In 1750, Gabriel Cramer used them for giving explicit solutions of linear systems, now called Cramer's rule.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Later, Gauss further described the method of elimination, which was initially listed as an advancement in geodesy.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In 1848, James Joseph Sylvester introduced the term *matrix*, which is Latin for *womb*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebra grew with ideas noted in the complex plane.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For instance, two numbers w and z in $\mathbb {C}$ have a difference *w* – *z*, and the line segments *wz* and 0(*w* − *z*) are of the same length and direction.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The four-dimensional system $\mathbb {H}$ of quaternions was discovered by W.R.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The term *vector* was introduced as **v** = *x***i** + *y***j** + *z***k** representing a point in space.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The quaternion difference *p* – *q* also produces a segment equipollent to *pq*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Other hypercomplex number systems also used the idea of a linear space with a basis.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Arthur Cayley introduced matrix multiplication and the inverse matrix in 1856, making possible the general linear group.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The mechanism of group representation became available for describing complex and hypercomplex numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Crucially, Cayley used a single letter to denote a matrix, thus treating a matrix as an aggregate object.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] He also realized the connection between matrices and determinants and wrote "There would be many things to say about this theory of matrices which should, it seems to me, precede the theory of determinants".
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Benjamin Peirce published his *Linear Associative Algebra* (1872), and his son Charles Sanders Peirce extended the work later.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The telegraph required an explanatory system, and the 1873 publication by James Clerk Maxwell of *A Treatise on Electricity and Magnetism* instituted a field theory of forces and required differential geometry for expression.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is flat differential geometry and serves in tangent spaces to manifolds.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Electromagnetic symmetries of spacetime are expressed by the Lorentz transformations, and much of the history of linear algebra is the history of Lorentz transformations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The first modern and more precise definition of a vector space was introduced by Peano in 1888; by 1900, a theory of linear transformations of finite-dimensional vector spaces had emerged.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebra took its modern form in the first half of the twentieth century when many ideas and methods of previous centuries were generalized as abstract algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The development of computers led to increased research in efficient algorithms for Gaussian elimination and matrix decompositions, and linear algebra became an essential tool for modeling and simulations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Until the 19th century, linear algebra was introduced through systems of linear equations and matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In modern mathematics, the presentation through *vector spaces* is generally preferred, since it is more synthetic, more general (not limited to the finite-dimensional case), and conceptually simpler, although more abstract.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A vector space over a field *F* (often the field of the real numbers or of the complex numbers) is a set *V* equipped with two binary operations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Elements of *V* are called *vectors*, and elements of *F* are called *scalars*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The first operation, *vector addition*, takes any two vectors **v** and **w** and outputs a third vector **v** + **w**.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The second operation, *scalar multiplication*, takes any scalar *a* and any vector **v** and outputs a new vector *a***v**.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The axioms that addition and scalar multiplication must satisfy are the following.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The first four axioms mean that *V* is an abelian group under addition.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The elements of a specific vector space may have various natures; for example, they could be tuples, sequences, functions, polynomials, or matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is concerned with the properties of such objects that are common to all vector spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] for any vectors **u**,**v** in *V* and scalar *a* in F.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] for any vectors **u**, **v** in *V* and scalars *a*, *b* in F.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] When *V* = *W* are the same vector space, a linear map *T* : *V* → *V* is also known as a *linear operator* on V.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A bijective linear map between two vector spaces (that is, every vector from the second space is associated with exactly one in the first) is an isomorphism.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Because an isomorphism preserves linear structure, two isomorphic vector spaces are "essentially the same" from the linear algebra point of view, in the sense that they cannot be distinguished by using vector space properties.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] An essential question in linear algebra is testing whether a linear map is an isomorphism or not, and, if it is not an isomorphism, finding its range (or image) and the set of elements that are mapped to the zero vector, called the kernel of the map.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] All these questions can be solved by using Gaussian elimination or some variant of this algorithm.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The study of those subsets of vector spaces that are in themselves vector spaces under the induced operations is fundamental, similarly as for many mathematical structures.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] These subsets are called linear subspaces.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] More precisely, a linear subspace of a vector space V over a field F is a subset W of V such that **u** + **v** and *a***u** are in W, for every **u**, **v** in W, and every a in F.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For example, given a linear map *T* : *V* → *W*, the image *T*(*V*) of V, and the inverse image *T*−1(**0**) of **0** (called kernel or null space), are linear subspaces of W and V, respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The span of S is also the intersection of all linear subspaces containing S.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In other words, it is the smallest (for the inclusion relation) linear subspace containing S.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A set of vectors is linearly independent if none is in the span of the others.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Equivalently, a set S of vectors is linearly independent if the only way to express the zero vector as a linear combination of elements of S is to take zero for every coefficient ai.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A set of vectors that spans a vector space is called a spanning set or generating set.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If a spanning set S is *linearly dependent* (that is not linearly independent), then some element **w** of S is in the span of the other elements of S, and the span would remain the same if one were to remove **w** from S.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] One may continue to remove elements of S until getting a *linearly independent spanning set*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Such a linearly independent set that spans a vector space V is called a basis of *V*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The importance of bases lies in the fact that they are simultaneously minimal-generating sets and maximal independent sets.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] More precisely, if S is a linearly independent set, and T is a spanning set such that *S* ⊆ *T*, then there is a basis B such that *S* ⊆ *B* ⊆ *T*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Any two bases of a vector space *V* have the same cardinality, which is called the dimension of *V*; this is the dimension theorem for vector spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Moreover, two vector spaces over the same field F are isomorphic if and only if they have the same dimension.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If any basis of *V* (and therefore every basis) has a finite number of elements, *V* is a *finite-dimensional vector space*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If *U* is a subspace of *V*, then dim *U* ≤ dim *V*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In the case where *V* is finite-dimensional, the equality of the dimensions implies *U* = *V*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Matrices allow explicit manipulation of finite-dimensional vector spaces and linear maps.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Their theory is thus an essential part of linear algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Let V be a finite-dimensional vector space over a field *F*, and (**v**1, **v**2, ..., **v***m*) be a basis of *V* (thus m is the dimension of *V*).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] is a bijection from *Fm*, the set of the sequences of m elements of F, onto V.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This is an isomorphism of vector spaces, if *Fm* is equipped with its standard structure of vector space, where vector addition and scalar multiplication are done component by component.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If W is another finite dimensional vector space (possibly the same), with a basis (**w**1, ..., **w***n*), a linear map f from W to V is well defined by its values on the basis elements, that is (*f*(**w**1), ..., *f*(**w***n*)).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Thus, f is well represented by the list of the corresponding column matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It follows that the theory of finite-dimensional vector spaces and the theory of matrices are two different languages for expressing the same concepts.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Two matrices that encode the same linear transformation in different bases are called similar.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It can be proven that two matrices are similar if and only if one can transform one into the other by elementary row and column operations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For a matrix representing a linear map from W to V, the row operations correspond to change of bases in V and the column operations correspond to change of bases in W.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Every matrix is similar to an identity matrix possibly bordered by zero rows and zero columns.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In terms of vector spaces, this means that, for any linear map from W to V, there are bases such that a part of the basis of W is mapped bijectively on a part of the basis of V, and that the remaining basis elements of W, if any, are mapped to zero.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Gaussian elimination is the basic algorithm for finding these elementary operations, and proving these results.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A finite set of linear equations in a finite set of variables, for example, *x*1, *x*2, ..., *xn*, or *x*, *y*, ..., *z* is called a **system of linear equations** or a **linear system**.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Systems of linear equations form a fundamental part of linear algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Historically, linear algebra and matrix theory have been developed for solving such systems.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In the modern presentation of linear algebra through vector spaces and matrices, many problems may be interpreted in terms of linear systems.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Let T be the linear transformation associated with the matrix M.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] that is an element of the preimage of v by T.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The solutions of (**S′**) are exactly the elements of the kernel of T or, equivalently, M.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] for putting it in reduced row echelon form.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] These row operations do not change the set of solutions of the system of equations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If $m=n$ and the matrix A is invertible, then the system has the unique solution $\mathbf {x} =A^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It follows from this matrix interpretation of linear systems that the same methods can be applied for solving linear systems and for many operations on matrices and linear transformations, which include the computation of the ranks, kernels, matrix inverses.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A linear endomorphism is a linear map that maps a vector space V to itself.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If V has a basis of n elements, such an endomorphism is represented by a square matrix of size n.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] where *Sn* is the group of all permutations of n elements, σ is a permutation, and (−1)*σ* the parity of the permutation.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A matrix is invertible if and only if the determinant is invertible (i.e., nonzero if the scalars belong to a field).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Cramer's rule is a closed-form expression, in terms of determinants, of the solution of a system of n linear equations in n unknowns.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Cramer's rule is useful for reasoning about the solution, but, except for *n* = 2 or 3, it is rarely used for computing a solution, since Gaussian elimination is a faster algorithm.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The *determinant of an endomorphism* is the determinant of the matrix representing the endomorphism in terms of some ordered basis.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This definition makes sense since this determinant is independent of the choice of the basis.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If f is a linear endomorphism of a vector space V over a field F, an *eigenvector* of f is a nonzero vector v of V such that *f*(*v*) = *av* for some scalar a in F.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] As z is supposed to be nonzero, this means that *M* – *aI* is a singular matrix, and thus that its determinant det (*M* − *aI*) equals zero.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If V is of dimension n, this is a monic polynomial of degree n, called the characteristic polynomial of the matrix (or of the endomorphism), and there are, at most, n eigenvalues.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If a basis exists that consists only of eigenvectors, the matrix of f on this basis has a very simple structure: it is a diagonal matrix such that the entries on the main diagonal are eigenvalues, and the other entries are zero.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In this case, the endomorphism and the matrix are said to be diagonalizable.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] More generally, an endomorphism and a matrix are also said diagonalizable, if they become diagonalizable after extending the field of scalars.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In this extended sense, if the characteristic polynomial is square-free, then the matrix is diagonalizable.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A symmetric matrix is always diagonalizable.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] (it cannot be diagonalizable since its square is the zero matrix, and the square of a nonzero diagonal matrix is never zero).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] When an endomorphism is not diagonalizable, there are bases on which it has a simple form, although not as simple as the diagonal form.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The Frobenius normal form does not need to extend the field of scalars and makes the characteristic polynomial immediately readable on the matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The Jordan normal form requires to extension of the field of scalar for containing all eigenvalues and differs from the diagonal form only by some entries that are just above the main diagonal and are equal to 1.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A linear form is a linear map from a vector space V over a field F to the field of scalars F, viewed as a vector space over itself.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Equipped by pointwise addition and multiplication by a scalar, the linear forms form a vector space, called the **dual space** of V, and usually denoted V* or V′.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] These linear maps form a basis of *V**, called the dual basis of **v**1, ..., **v***n*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This defines the canonical linear map from V into (*V**)*, the dual of V*, called the **double dual** or **bidual** of V.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This canonical map is an isomorphism if V is finite-dimensional, and this allows identifying V with its bidual.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] There is thus a complete symmetry between a finite-dimensional vector space and its dual.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For every linear form h on W, the composite function *h* ∘ *f* is a linear form on V.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] between the dual spaces, which is called the **dual** or the **transpose** of f.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If V and W are finite-dimensional, and M is the matrix of f in terms of some ordered bases, then the matrix of f* over the dual bases is the transpose *M*T of M, obtained by exchanging rows and columns.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Besides these basic concepts, linear algebra also studies vector spaces with additional structure, such as an inner product.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The inner product is an example of a bilinear form, and it gives the vector space a geometric structure by allowing for the definition of length and angles.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] and so we can call this quantity the cosine of the angle between the two vectors.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] An orthonormal basis is a basis where all basis vectors have length 1 and are orthogonal to each other.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Given any finite-dimensional vector space, an orthonormal basis could be found by the Gram–Schmidt procedure.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The inner product facilitates the construction of many useful concepts.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] If *T* satisfies *TT** = *T*T*, we call *T* normal.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It turns out that normal matrices are precisely the matrices that have an orthonormal system of eigenvectors that span *V*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] There is a strong relationship between linear algebra and geometry, which started with the introduction by René Descartes, in 1637, of Cartesian coordinates.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In this new (at that time) geometry, now called Cartesian geometry, points are represented by Cartesian coordinates, which are sequences of three real numbers (in the case of the usual three-dimensional space).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The basic objects of geometry, which are lines and planes are represented by linear equations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Thus, computing intersections of lines and planes amounts to solving systems of linear equations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This was one of the main motivations for developing linear algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Most geometric transformation, such as translations, rotations, reflections, rigid motions, isometries, and projections transform lines into lines.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It follows that they can be defined, specified, and studied in terms of linear maps.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This is also the case of homographies and Möbius transformations when considered as transformations of a projective space.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Until the end of the 19th century, geometric spaces were defined by axioms relating points, lines, and planes (synthetic geometry).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Around this date, it appeared that one may also define geometric spaces by constructions involving vector spaces (see, for example, Projective space and Affine space).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It has been shown that the two approaches are essentially equivalent.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In classical geometry, the involved vector spaces are vector spaces over the reals, but the constructions may be extended to vector spaces over any field, allowing considering geometry over arbitrary fields, including finite fields.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Presently, most textbooks introduce geometric spaces from linear algebra, and geometry is often presented, at the elementary level, as a subfield of linear algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is used in almost all areas of mathematics, thus making it relevant in almost all scientific domains that use mathematics.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] These applications may be divided into several wide categories.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Functional analysis studies function spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] These are vector spaces with additional structure, such as Hilbert spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is thus a fundamental part of functional analysis and its applications, which include, in particular, quantum mechanics (wave functions) and Fourier analysis (orthogonal basis).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Nearly all scientific computations involve linear algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Consequently, linear algebra algorithms have been highly optimized.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] BLAS and LAPACK are the best known implementations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For improving efficiency, some of them configure the algorithms automatically, at run time, to adapt them to the specificities of the computer (cache size, number of available cores, ...).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Since the 1960s there have been processors with specialized instructions for optimizing the operations of linear algebra, optional array processors under the control of a conventional processor, supercomputers designed for array processing and conventional processors augmented with vector registers.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Some contemporary processors, typically graphics processing units (GPU), are designed with a matrix structure, for optimizing the operations of linear algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The modeling of ambient space is based on geometry.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Sciences concerned with this space use geometry widely.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This is the case with mechanics and robotics, for describing rigid body dynamics; geodesy for describing Earth shape; perspectivity, computer vision, and computer graphics, for describing the relationship between a scene and its plane representation; and many other scientific domains.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In all these applications, synthetic geometry is often used for general descriptions and a qualitative approach, but for the study of explicit situations, one must compute with coordinates.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This requires the heavy use of linear algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Most physical phenomena are modeled by partial differential equations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] To solve them, one usually decomposes the space in which the solutions are searched into small, mutually interacting cells.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For linear systems this interaction involves linear functions.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For nonlinear systems, this interaction is often approximated by linear functions.This is called a linear model or first-order approximation.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear models are frequently used for complex nonlinear real-world systems because they make parametrization more manageable.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In both cases, very large matrices are generally involved.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Weather forecasting (or more specifically, parametrization for atmospheric modeling) is a typical example of a real-world application, where the whole Earth atmosphere is divided into cells of, say, 100 km of width and 100 km of height.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebra, a branch of mathematics dealing with vector spaces and linear mappings between these spaces, plays a critical role in various engineering disciplines, including fluid mechanics, fluid dynamics, and thermal energy systems.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Its application in these fields is multifaceted and indispensable for solving complex problems.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In fluid mechanics, linear algebra is integral to understanding and solving problems related to the behavior of fluids.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It assists in the modeling and simulation of fluid flow, providing essential tools for the analysis of fluid dynamics problems.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For instance, linear algebraic techniques are used to solve systems of differential equations that describe fluid motion.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] These equations, often complex and non-linear, can be linearized using linear algebra methods, allowing for simpler solutions and analyses.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In the field of fluid dynamics, linear algebra finds its application in computational fluid dynamics (CFD), a branch that uses numerical analysis and data structures to solve and analyze problems involving fluid flows.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] CFD relies heavily on linear algebra for the computation of fluid flow and heat transfer in various applications.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For example, the Navier–Stokes equations, fundamental in fluid dynamics, are often solved using techniques derived from linear algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This includes the use of matrices and vectors to represent and manipulate fluid flow fields.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Furthermore, linear algebra plays a crucial role in thermal energy systems, particularly in power systems analysis.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It is used to model and optimize the generation, transmission, and distribution of electric power.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Linear algebraic concepts such as matrix operations and eigenvalue problems are employed to enhance the efficiency, reliability, and economic performance of power systems.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The application of linear algebra in this context is vital for the design and operation of modern power systems, including renewable energy sources and smart grids.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Overall, the application of linear algebra in fluid mechanics, fluid dynamics, and thermal energy systems is an example of the profound interconnection between mathematics and engineering.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It provides engineers with the necessary tools to model, analyze, and solve complex problems in these domains, leading to advancements in technology and industry.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This section presents several related topics that do not appear generally in elementary textbooks on linear algebra but are commonly considered, in advanced mathematics, as parts of linear algebra.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The existence of multiplicative inverses in fields is not involved in the axioms defining a vector space.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] One may thus replace the field of scalars by a ring R, and this gives the structure called a **module** over R, or R-module.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The concepts of linear independence, span, basis, and linear maps (also called module homomorphisms) are defined for modules exactly as for vector spaces, with the essential difference that, if R is not a field, there are modules that do not have any basis.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The modules that have a basis are the free modules, and those that are spanned by a finite set are the finitely generated modules.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Module homomorphisms between finitely generated free modules may be represented by matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The theory of matrices over a ring is similar to that of matrices over a field, except that determinants exist only if the ring is commutative, and that a square matrix over a commutative ring is invertible only if its determinant has a multiplicative inverse in the ring.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Vector spaces are completely characterized by their dimension (up to an isomorphism).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In general, there is not such a complete classification for modules, even if one restricts oneself to finitely generated modules.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] However, every module is a cokernel of a homomorphism of free modules.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Modules over the integers can be identified with abelian groups, since the multiplication by an integer may be identified as a repeated addition.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Most of the theory of abelian groups may be extended to modules over a principal ideal domain.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In particular, over a principal ideal domain, every submodule of a free module is free, and the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups may be extended straightforwardly to finitely generated modules over a principal ring.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] There are many rings for which there are algorithms for solving linear equations and systems of linear equations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] However, these algorithms have generally a computational complexity that is much higher than similar algorithms over a field.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] For more details, see Linear equation over a ring.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] In multilinear algebra, one considers multivariable linear transformations, that is, mappings that are linear in each of several different variables.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] This line of inquiry naturally leads to the idea of the dual space, the vector space *V** consisting of linear maps *f* : *V* → *F* where *F* is the field of scalars.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Multilinear maps *T* : *Vn* → *F* can be described via tensor products of elements of *V**.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Vector spaces that are not finite-dimensional often require additional structure to be tractable.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A normed vector space is a vector space along with a function called a norm, which measures the "size" of elements.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The norm induces a metric, which measures the distance between elements, and induces a topology, which allows for a definition of continuous maps.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] The metric also allows for a definition of limits and completeness – a normed vector space that is complete is known as a Banach space.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] A complete metric space along with the additional structure of an inner product (a conjugate symmetric sesquilinear form) is known as a Hilbert space, which is in some sense a particularly well-behaved Banach space.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] Functional analysis is of particular importance to quantum mechanics, the theory of partial differential equations, digital signal processing, and electrical engineering.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-algebra] It also provides the foundation and theoretical framework that underlies the Fourier transform and related methods.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] In mathematics, and more specifically in linear algebra, a **linear map** (or **linear mapping**) is a particular kind of function between vector spaces, which respects the basic operations of vector addition and scalar multiplication.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] A standard example of a linear map is an $m\times n$ matrix, which takes vectors in n -dimensions into vectors in m -dimensions in a way that is compatible with addition of vectors, and multiplication of vectors by scalars.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] A linear map is a homomorphism of vector spaces.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Thus, a linear map $T:V\to W$ satisfies ⁠ $T(ax+by)=aTx+bTy$ ⁠, where a and b are scalars, and x and y are vectors (elements of the vector space ⁠ V ⁠).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Linear maps can often be represented as matrices, and simple examples include rotation and reflection linear transformations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Let V and W be vector spaces over the same field ⁠ K ⁠, such as the real or complex numbers.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Thus, a linear map is said to be *operation preserving*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] In other words, it does not matter whether the linear map is applied before (the right sides of the above examples) or after (the left sides of the examples) the operations of addition and scalar multiplication.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Denoting the zero elements of the vector spaces V and W by ${\textstyle \mathbf {0} _{V}}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {0} _{W}}$ respectively, it follows that ⁠ $f(\mathbf {0} _{V})=\mathbf {0} _{W}$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] A linear map $V\to K$ with K viewed as a one-dimensional vector space over itself is called a linear functional.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] These statements generalize to any left-module ${\textstyle {}_{R}M}$ over a ring R without modification, and to any right-module upon reversing of the scalar multiplication.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] If a linear map is a bijection then it is called a **linear isomorphism**.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] In the case where ⁠ $V=W$ ⁠, a linear map is called a **linear endomorphism**.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Sometimes the term **linear operator** refers to this case, but the term "linear operator" can have different meanings for different conventions.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Often, a linear map is constructed by defining it on a subset of a vector space and then *extending by linearity* to the linear span of the domain.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Suppose X and Y are vector spaces and $f:S\to Y$ is a function defined on some subset ⁠ $S\subseteq X$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Then a *linear extension of f to $X,$* if it exists, is a linear map $F:X\to Y$ defined on X that extends f (meaning that $F(s)=f(s)$ for all ⁠ $s\in S$ ⁠) and takes its values from the codomain of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] When the subset S is a vector subspace of X then a (⁠ Y ⁠-valued) linear extension of f to all of X is guaranteed to exist if (and only if) $f:S\to Y$ is a linear map.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] In particular, if f has a linear extension to $\operatorname {span} S,$ then it has a linear extension to all of ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] If S is linearly independent then every function $f:S\to Y$ into any vector space has a linear extension to a (linear) map $\operatorname {span} S\to Y$ (the converse is also true).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Every (scalar-valued) linear functional f defined on a vector subspace of a real or complex vector space X has a linear extension to all of ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] If V and W are finite-dimensional vector spaces and a basis is defined for each vector space, then every linear map from V to W can be represented by a matrix.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] This is useful because it allows concrete calculations.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Matrices yield examples of linear maps: if A is a real $m\times n$ matrix, then $f(\mathbf {x} )=A\mathbf {x}$ describes a linear map $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ (see Euclidean space).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] which implies that the function *f* is entirely determined by the vectors ⁠ $f(\mathbf {v} _{1}),\ldots ,f(\mathbf {v} _{n})$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Thus, the function f is entirely determined by the values of ⁠ $a_{ij}$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] If we put these values into an $m\times n$ matrix ⁠ M ⁠, then we can conveniently use it to compute the vector output of f for any vector in ⁠ V ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] To get ⁠ M ⁠, every column j of M is a vector ${\begin{pmatrix}a_{1j}\\\vdots \\a_{mj}\end{pmatrix}}$ corresponding to $f(\mathbf {v} _{j})$ as defined above.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] To define it more clearly, for some column j that corresponds to the mapping ⁠ $f(\mathbf {v} _{j})$ ⁠, $\mathbf {M} ={\begin{pmatrix}\ \cdots &a_{1j}&\cdots \ \\&\vdots &\\&a_{mj}&\end{pmatrix}}$ where M is the matrix of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] In other words, every column $j=1,\ldots ,n$ has a corresponding vector $f(\mathbf {v} _{j})$ whose coordinates $a_{1j},\cdots ,a_{mj}$ are the elements of column ⁠ j ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] A single linear map may be represented by many matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] This is because the values of the elements of a matrix depend on the bases chosen.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The equivalent method would be the "longer" method going clockwise from the same point such that ${\textstyle \left[\mathbf {v} \right]_{B'}}$ is left-multiplied with ⁠ $P^{-1}AP$ ⁠, or ⁠ $\textstyle P^{-1}AP\left[\mathbf {v} \right]_{B'}=\left[T\left(\mathbf {v} \right)\right]_{B'}$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] In two-dimensional space **R**2 linear maps are described by 2 × 2 matrices.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] If a linear map is only composed of rotation, reflection, and/or uniform scaling, then the linear map is a conformal linear transformation.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The composition of linear maps is linear: if $f:V\to W$ and ${\textstyle g:W\to Z}$ are linear, then so is their composition ⁠ $g\circ f:V\to Z$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] It follows from this that the class of all vector spaces over a given field *K*, together with linear maps as morphisms, forms a category.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The inverse of a linear map, when defined, is again a linear map.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] If ${\textstyle f:V\to W}$ is linear and ${\textstyle \alpha }$ is an element of the ground field ⁠ K ⁠, then the map ⁠ $\alpha f$ ⁠, defined by ⁠ $(\alpha f)(\mathbf {x} )=\alpha (f(\mathbf {x} ))$ ⁠, is also linear.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Thus the set ${\textstyle {\mathcal {L}}(V,W)}$ of linear maps from ${\textstyle V}$ to ${\textstyle W}$ itself forms a vector space over ⁠ K ⁠, sometimes denoted ⁠ $\operatorname {Hom} (V,W)$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Furthermore, in the case that ⁠ $V=W$ ⁠, this vector space, denoted ⁠ $\operatorname {End} (V)$ ⁠, is an associative algebra under composition of maps, since the composition of two linear maps is again a linear map, and the composition of maps is always associative.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] This case is discussed in more detail below.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The multiplicative identity element of this algebra is the identity map ⁠ $\operatorname {id} :V\to V$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] An endomorphism of ${\textstyle V}$ that is also an isomorphism is called an automorphism of ⁠ V ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The composition of two automorphisms is again an automorphism, and the set of all automorphisms of ${\textstyle V}$ forms a group, the automorphism group of ${\textstyle V}$ which is denoted by ${\textstyle \operatorname {Aut} (V)}$ or ⁠ $\operatorname {GL} (V)$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Since the automorphisms are precisely those endomorphisms which possess inverses under composition, ${\textstyle \operatorname {Aut} (V)}$ is the group of units in the ring ⁠ $\operatorname {End} (V)$ ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] If ${\textstyle V}$ has finite dimension ⁠ n ⁠, then ${\textstyle \operatorname {End} (V)}$ is isomorphic to the associative algebra of all ${\textstyle n\times n}$ matrices with entries in ⁠ K ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The automorphism group of ${\textstyle V}$ is isomorphic to the general linear group ${\textstyle \operatorname {GL} (n,K)}$ of all ${\textstyle n\times n}$ invertible matrices with entries in ⁠ K ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] ${\textstyle \ker(f)}$ is a subspace of ${\textstyle V}$ and ${\textstyle \operatorname {im} (f)}$ is a subspace of ⁠ W ⁠.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] If ${\textstyle V}$ and ${\textstyle W}$ are finite-dimensional, bases have been chosen and ${\textstyle f}$ is represented by the matrix ⁠ A ⁠, then the rank and nullity of ${\textstyle f}$ are equal to the rank and nullity of the matrix ⁠ A ⁠, respectively.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The dimension of the co-kernel and the dimension of the image (the rank) add up to the dimension of the target space.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] For finite dimensions, this means that the dimension of the quotient space *W* / *f*(*V*) is the dimension of the target space minus the dimension of the image.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Then for an equation *f*(*x*, *y*) = (*a*, *b*) to have a solution, we must have *a* = 0 (one constraint), and in that case the solution space is (*x*, *b*) or equivalently stated, (0, *b*) + (*x*, 0), (one degree of freedom).
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The kernel may be expressed as the subspace (*x*, 0) < *V*: the value of *x* is the freedom in a solution – while the cokernel may be expressed via the map *W* → **R**, ⁠ $(a,b)\mapsto (a)$ ⁠: given a vector (*a*, *b*), the value of *a* is the *obstruction* to there being a solution.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] An example illustrating the infinite-dimensional case is afforded by the map *f* : **R**∞ → **R**∞, ${\textstyle \left\{a_{n}\right\}\mapsto \left\{b_{n}\right\}}$ with *b*1 = 0 and *b**n* + 1 = *an* for *n* > 0.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Its image consists of all sequences with first element 0, and thus its cokernel consists of the classes of sequences with identical first element.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Thus, whereas its kernel has dimension 0 (it maps only the zero sequence to the zero sequence), its co-kernel has dimension 1.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Its image is the entire target space, and hence its co-kernel has dimension 0, but since it maps all sequences in which only the first element is non-zero to the zero sequence, its kernel has dimension 1.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] For a linear operator with finite-dimensional kernel and co-kernel, one may define *index* as: $\operatorname {ind} (f):=\dim(\ker(f))-\dim(\operatorname {coker} (f)),$ namely the degrees of freedom minus the number of constraints.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] For a transformation between finite-dimensional vector spaces, this is just the difference dim(*V*) − dim(*W*), by rank–nullity.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] This gives an indication of how many solutions or how many constraints one has: if mapping from a larger space to a smaller one, the map may be onto, and thus will have degrees of freedom even without constraints.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Conversely, if mapping from a smaller space to a larger one, the map cannot be onto, and thus one will have constraints even without degrees of freedom.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The index of an operator is precisely the Euler characteristic of the 2-term complex 0 → *V* → *W* → 0.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] In operator theory, the index of Fredholm operators is an object of study, with a major result being the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] No classification of linear maps could be exhaustive.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] The following incomplete list enumerates some important classifications that do not require any additional structure on the vector space.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Let V and W denote vector spaces over a field F and let *T* : *V* → *W* be a linear map.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] T is monic or left-cancellable, which is to say, for any vector space U and any pair of linear maps *R*: *U* → *V* and *S* : *U* → *V*, the equation *TR* = *TS* implies *R* = *S*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] T is left-invertible, which is to say there exists a linear map *S* : *W* → *V* such that *ST* is the identity map on V.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] T is epic or right-cancellable, which is to say, for any vector space U and any pair of linear maps *R* : *W* → *U* and *S* : *W* → *U*, the equation *RT* = *ST* implies *R* = *S*.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] T is right-invertible, which is to say there exists a linear map *S* : *W* → *V* such that *TS* is the identity map on W.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] T is said to be an *isomorphism* if it is both left- and right-invertible.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] This is equivalent to T being both one-to-one and onto (a bijection of sets) or also to T being both epic and monic, and so being a bimorphism.
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Given a linear map which is an endomorphism whose matrix is *A*, in the basis *B* of the space it transforms vector coordinates [*u*] as [*v*] = *A*[*u*].
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] As vectors change with the inverse of *B* (vectors coordinates are contravariant) its inverse transformation is [*v*] = *B*[*v*′].
[src:linear-algebra/linear-map] Therefore, the matrix in the new basis is *A*′ = *B*−1*AB*, being *B* the matrix of the given basis.
